# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anti-nuclear-movement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research into this topic is fairly new, with few studies published before 2009, but has gained increasing attention in recent years.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A cross-sectoral, holistic approach is seen as an important feature of 100% renewable energy systems and is based on the assumption "that the best solutions can be found only if one focuses on the synergies between the sectors" of the energy system such as electricity, heat, transport or industry.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] No uniform definition for 100% renewable energy systems has been adopted across the published literature.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Recent studies show that a global transition to 100% renewable energy across all sectors – power, heat, transport and desalination well before 2050 is feasible.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Existing technologies, including storage, are capable of generating a secure energy supply at every hour throughout the year.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The sustainable energy system is more efficient and cost effective than the existing system.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) stated in their 2011 report that there is little that limits integrating renewable technologies for satisfying the total global energy demand.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Barriers to implementing the renewable energy plan are seen to be "primarily social and political, not technological or economic".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main obstacle against this scenario is the lack of political will.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] His conclusions have been disputed by other researchers.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson published a response that disputed the piece point by point and claimed that the authors were motivated by allegiance to energy technologies that the 2015 paper excluded.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies and he has rebutted their criticisms.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A followup paper was published by Jacobson and others in 2022, in which paths to 100% renewable energy by 2035 and 2050 were developed for 145 countries.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study concluded that a wind-water-solar (WWS) based system "requires less energy, costs less, and creates more jobs than business as usual".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The cost reduction was primarily due to the substantial (-56.4%) decrease in overall energy demand thanks to the increased efficiency of relying on renewable electricity for all energy needs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2014, renewable sources such as wind, geothermal, solar, biomass, and burnt waste provided 19% of the total energy consumed worldwide, with roughly half of that coming from traditional use of biomass.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest sector in terms of energy consumption is electricity with a renewable share of 22.8%, most of it coming from hydropower with a share of 16.6%, followed by wind with 3.1%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018, according to REN21, transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy .
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] At the national level, at least 30 nations already have renewable energy contributing more than 20% of the energy supply.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown more quickly than even advocates anticipated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2019, however, it needs to grow six times faster to limit global warming to 2 °C (3.6 °F).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] 100% renewable energy in a country is typically a more challenging goal than carbon neutrality.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The latter is a climate mitigation target, politically decided by many countries, and may also be achieved by balancing the total carbon footprint of the country (not only emissions from energy and fuel) with carbon dioxide removal and carbon projects abroad.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018 according to REN21 transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow of Princeton University have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow us to maintain our quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low-carbon energy strategies are political rather than technological.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the 2013 *Post Carbon Pathways* report, which reviewed many international studies, the key roadblocks are: climate change denial, the fossil fuels lobby, political inaction, unsustainable energy consumption, outdated energy infrastructure, and financial constraints.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Studies have shown that Southeast Asia countries could achieve almost 100% renewable elecitricity based on solar, wind, and off-river pumped hydro energy storage at a competitive LCOE of around US$55–115/MWh.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Using 100% renewable energy was first suggested in a paper in *Science* published in 1975 by Danish physicist Bent Sørensen, which was followed by several other proposals.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1976, energy policy analyst Amory Lovins coined the term "soft energy path" to describe an alternative future where energy efficiency and appropriate renewable energy sources steadily replace a centralized energy system based on fossil and nuclear fuels.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1998, the first detailed analysis of scenarios with high shares of renewables were published.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] These were followed by the first detailed 100% scenarios.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2006, a PhD thesis was published by Czisch in which it was shown that in a 100% renewable scenario energy supply could match demand in every hour of the year in Europe and North Africa.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, Danish Energy professor Henrik Lund published a first paper in which he addresses the optimal combination of renewables, which was followed by several other papers on the transition to 100% renewable energy in Denmark.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Since then, Lund has been publishing several papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] After 2009, publications began to rise steeply, covering 100% scenarios for countries in Europe, America, Australia and other parts of the world.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Even in the early 21st century, it was extraordinary for scientists and decision-makers to consider the concept of 100% renewable electricity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown much faster than even advocates had anticipated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Wind turbines generate 39 percent of Danish electricity, and Denmark has many biogas digesters and waste-to-energy plants as well.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Together, wind and biomass provide 44% of the electricity consumed by the country's six million inhabitants.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2010, Portugal's 10 million people produced more than half their electricity from indigenous renewable energy resources.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Spain's 40 million inhabitants meet one-third of their electrical needs from renewables.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy has a history of strong public support.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In America, for example, a 2013 Gallup survey showed that two in three Americans want the U.S. to increase domestic energy production using solar power (76%), wind power (71%), and natural gas (65%).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Far fewer want more petroleum production (46%) and more nuclear power (37%).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Least favored is coal, with about one in three Americans favouring it.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supporters of 100% renewable energy do not consider nuclear power as renewable or sustainable due to perceived risks of disasters and high-level waste management, and consider carbon capture and storage to have limited safe storage potential.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] These constraints have also led to an interest in 100% renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A well established body of academic literature has been written over the past decade, evaluating scenarios for 100% renewable energy for various geographical areas.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In recent years, more detailed analyses have emerged from government and industry sources.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The incentive to use 100% renewable energy is created by global warming and ecological as well as economic concerns, post peak oil.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The first country to propose 100% renewable energy was Iceland, in 1998.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Proposals have been made for Japan in 2003, and for Australia in 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania, Iceland, and Paraguay obtain essentially all of their electricity from renewable sources (Albania and Paraguay 100% from hydroelectricity, Iceland 72% hydro and 28% geothermal).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Norway obtains nearly all of its electricity from renewable sources (97 percent from hydropower).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Iceland proposed using hydrogen for transportation and its fishing fleet.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Australia proposed biofuel for those elements of transportation not easily converted to electricity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The road map for the United States, commitment by Denmark, and Vision 2050 for Europe set a 2050 timeline for converting to 100% renewable energy, later reduced to 2040 in 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Zero Carbon Britain 2030 proposes eliminating carbon emissions in Britain by 2030 by transitioning to renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2015, Hawaii enacted a law that the Renewable Portfolio Standard shall be 100 percent by 2045.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] This is often confused with renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] If electricity produced on the grid is 65 GWh from fossil fuel and 35 GWh from renewable energy and rooftop off grid solar produces 80 GWh of renewable energy, then the total renewable energy is 115 GWh and the total electricity on the grid is 100 GWh.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Cities like Paris and Strasbourg in France, planned to use 100% renewable energy by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] It is estimated that the world will spend an extra $8 trillion over the next 25 years to prolong the use of non-renewable resources, a cost that would be eliminated by transitioning instead to 100% renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research that has been published in Energy Policy suggests that converting the entire world to 100% renewable energy by 2050 is both possible and affordable, but requires political support.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] It would require building many more wind turbines and solar power systems but wouldn't utilize bioenergy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other changes involve use of electric cars and the development of enhanced transmission grids and storage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] As part of the Paris Agreement, countries periodically update their climate change targets for the future, by 2018 no G20 country had committed to a 100% renewable target.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Until 2018, there were 181 peer-reviewed papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, 100% renewable energy was also mentioned in the Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5 °C as a potential means to "expand the range of 1.5 °C pathways", if the findings can be corroborated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2021, wind and solar were consistently increasing their share worldwide, but still represented just 5% of global primary energy consumption, albeit far more of useful energy consumption.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Morgan Asset Management (the biggest lender to fossil fuels in the world) analyzed renewable energy forecasts made by eight scientists and research bodies (including Bent Sorensen, Mark Z.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, Amory Lovins) between 1970 and 2020 and claimed that all of them were unrealistically optimistic as they ignored "energy density, intermittency and the complex realities of incumbent energy systems".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some other places have high percentages, for example the electricity sector in Denmark, as of 2014, is 45% wind power, with plans in place to reach 85%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The electricity sector in Canada and the electricity sector in New Zealand have even higher percentages of renewables (mostly hydro), 65% and 75% respectively, and Austria is approaching 70%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2015, the electricity sector in Germany sometimes meets almost 100% of the electricity demand with PV and wind power, and renewable electricity is over 25%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania has 94.8% of installed capacity as hydroelectric, 5.2% diesel generator; but Albania imports 39% of its electricity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2016, Portugal achieved 100% renewable electricity for four days between 7 and 11 May, partly because efficient energy use had reduced electricity demand.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] France and Sweden have low carbon intensity, since they predominantly use a mixture of nuclear power and hydroelectricity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018 Scotland met 76% of their demand from renewable sources.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Although electricity is currently around a quarter of world energy supply and consumption; primary energy use is expected to decrease with renewable energy deployment as electricity use increases, as it is likely to be combined with some degree of further electrification.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, electric cars achieve much better fuel efficiency than fossil fuel cars, and another example is renewable heat such as in the case of Denmark, which is proposing to move to greater use of heat pumps for heating buildings to provide multiple kilowatts of heat per kilowatt of electricity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other electricity generating sources are considered clean, though not necessarily renewable, as they also do not emit carbon dioxide or other greenhouse gases and air pollutants.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest of these is nuclear energy, which produces no emissions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some argue that transitioning to 100% renewable energy would be too slow to limit climate change, and that closing down nuclear power stations is a mistake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Carbon capture and storage projects may still use coal or natural gas but capture carbon dioxide for storage or alternative uses.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Pathways to eliminate greenhouse gases may include these in addition to renewable energy to save money, or to avoid shutting down existing plants and allow for flexibility in designing a carbon-free electric grid.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018, California passed SB 100, which mandates 100% clean, carbon-free by 2045, including a 60% renewable electricity goal by 2030.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] 2019 legislation in Washington also requires 100% clean electricity by 2045, eliminating coal by 2025.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Further states and territories to require 100% carbon-free electricity are Hawaii, Maine, Minnesota, Nevada, New Mexico, New York, Virginia, Puerto Rico, and Washington, DC.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to a study by Global Energy Monitor, China is expected to generate 1,200 gigawatts of renewable energy (wind and solar) by 2025.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, the most significant barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low carbon energy strategies, at the pace required to prevent runaway climate change, are primarily political and not technological.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] IPCC scenarios "generally indicate that growth in renewable energy will be widespread around the world".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The IPCC said that if governments were supportive, and the full complement of renewable energy technologies were deployed, renewable energy supply could account for almost 80% of the world's energy use within forty years.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Rajendra Pachauri, chairman of the IPCC, said the necessary investment in renewables would cost only about 1% of global GDP annually.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] This approach could contain greenhouse gas levels to less than 450 parts per million, the safe level beyond which climate change becomes catastrophic and irreversible.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow societies to maintain their quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown founder and president of the Earth Policy Institute, a nonprofit research organization based in Washington, D.C., says a rapid transition to 100% renewable energy is both possible and necessary.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown compares with the U.S. entry into World War II and the subsequent rapid mobilization and transformation of the US industry and economy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A quick transition to 100% renewable energy and saving of our civilization is proposed by Brown to follow an approach with similar urgency.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to World Bank the "below 2°C" climate scenario requires 3 billions of tonnes of metals and minerals by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supply of mined resources such as zinc, molybdenum, silver, nickel, copper must increase by up to 500%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A 2018 study analysed the metal requirements to transition the global energy system up to 2060.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Currently used battery technologies and known reserves are not compatible with the transition scenario as a result of insufficient cobalt and lithium reserves.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Batteries containing less or no cobalt are feasible.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Lithium is much more difficult to replace with maintained performance and cost.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review suggests large institutions are prone to resisting "the challenge of 100% RE scenarios based on the dogma that the world cannot do without fossil fuels and nuclear energy".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Institutions that have received extensive criticism include the International Energy Agency and the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, with the latter also being criticized for not including studies on 100% RE systems in their IPCC reports.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A report found that China is about to produce "almost 95% of the world's polysilicon and the ingots and wafers" of the solar panel supply chain, with this level of concentration in any global supply chain "would represent a considerable vulnerability".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] One of the main obstacles to 100% renewable energy is the intermittency or variability of renewable energy sources – such as times when sufficient amounts of energy can be generated neither via wind nor via solar power ("Dunkelflauten").
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to Amory Lovins the electricity grid alone can compensate for variability, just as it routinely backs up nonworking coal-fired and nuclear plants with working ones.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, it may cost 40% more to reduce carbon emissions without carbon dioxide capture.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study introduced the term "firm low-carbon energy source" (e.g. nuclear, geothermal), which is intended to operate along "fast-burst" sources (e.g. batteries) and "fuel saving" (VRE).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] The International Energy Agency says that there has been too much attention on issue of the variability of renewable electricity production.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Variability is rarely a barrier to increased renewable energy deployment when dispatchable generation such as hydroelectricity or solar thermal storage is also available.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] But at high levels of market penetration it requires careful analysis and management, and additional costs may be required for back-up or system modification.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Hydropower is currently the only large scale low-carbon seasonal energy storage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In countries with high variation in energy demand by season (for example the UK uses far more gas for heating in the winter than it uses electricity) but lacking hydropower electrical interconnectors to countries with lots of hydropower (e.g.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] UK - Norway), electricity from hydropower is likely to be insufficient and development of a hydrogen economy would likely be needed: this is being trialled in the UK and 8 TWh of inter-seasonal hydrogen energy storage has been proposed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] In Australia, as well as storing renewable energy as hydrogen, it is also proposed to be exported in the form of ammonia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] McKinsey estimates that it will cost 7.5% of global domestic product between 2021 and 2050 to achieve net zero (not 100% renewable, which will be more expensive).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Current spending is just over half of this.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review identified major gaps and neglected aspects – open research questions – in the 100% RE literature.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] Full decaronization of the energy system by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p01] 7.16 for renewable target and 12 for national target.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has said that there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a 2011 review of 164 recent scenarios of future renewable energy growth, the report noted that the majority expected renewable sources to supply more than 17% of total energy by 2030, and 27% by 2050; the highest forecast projected 43% supplied by renewables by 2030 and 77% by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2011, the refereed journal *Energy Policy* published two articles by Mark Z.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson, a professor of engineering at Stanford University, and research scientist Mark A.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Delucchi, about changing the energy supply mix and "Providing all global energy with wind, water, and solar power".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The articles analyze the feasibility of providing worldwide energy for electric power, transportation, and heating/cooling from wind, water, and sunlight (WWS), which are safe clean options.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part I, Jacobson and Delucchi discuss WWS energy system characteristics, aspects of energy demand, WWS resource availability, WWS devices needed, and material requirements.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] They estimate that 3,800,000 5 MW wind turbines, 5350 100 MW geothermal power plants, and 270 new 1300 MW hydroelectric power plants would be required.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In terms of solar power, an additional 49,000 300 MW concentrating solar plants, 40,000 300 MW solar photovoltaic power plants, and 1.7 billion 3 kW rooftop photovoltaic systems would also be needed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Such an extensive WWS infrastructure could decrease world power demand by 30%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part II, Jacobson and Delucchi address variability of supply, system economics, and energy policy initiatives associated with a WWS system.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The authors advocate producing all new energy with WWS by 2030 and replacing existing energy supply arrangements by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Energy costs with a WWS system should be similar to today's energy costs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In general, Jacobson has said wind, water and solar technologies can provide 100 percent of the world's energy, eliminating all fossil fuels.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] 0.1% of the time would require generation from other sources.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In March 2012, Denmark's parliament agreed on a comprehensive new set of promotional programs for energy efficiency and renewable energy aimed at reaching 100 percent of electricity, heat and fuels from renewables by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] IRENEC is an annual conference on 100% renewable energy started in 2011 by Eurosolar Turkey.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] More recently, Jacobson and his colleagues have developed detailed proposals for switching to 100% renewable energy produced by wind, water and sunlight, for New York, California and Washington states, by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] As of 2014, a more expansive new plan for the 50 states has been drawn up, which includes an online interactive map showing the renewable resource potential of each of the 50 states.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The 50-state plan is part of The Solutions Project, an independent outreach effort led by Jacobson, actor Mark Ruffalo, and film director Josh Fox.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Debate over detailed plans remain, but transformations in global energy services based entirely around renewable energy are in principle technically practicable, economically feasible, socially viable, and so realisable.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] This prospect underpins the ambitious commitment by Germany, one of the world's most successful industrial economies, to undertake a major energy transition, Energiewende.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015 a study was published in *Energy and Environmental Science* that describes a pathway to 100% renewable energy in the United States by 2050 without using biomass.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Implementation of this roadmap is regarded as both environmentally and economically feasible and reasonable, as by 2050 it would save about $600 billion of health costs a year due to reduced air pollution and $3.3 trillion global warming costs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] This would translate in yearly cost savings per head of around $8300 compared to a business as usual pathway.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to that study, barriers that could hamper implementation are neither technical nor economic but social and political, as most people didn't know that benefits from such a transformation far exceeded the costs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In June 2017, twenty-one researchers published an article in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America* rejecting Jacobson's earlier *PNAS* article, accusing him of modeling errors and of using invalid modeling tools.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] They further asserted he made implausible assumptions through his reliance upon increasing national energy storage from 43 minutes to 7 weeks, increasing hydrogen production by 100,000%, and increasing hydropower by the equivalent of 600 Hoover Dams.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Victor called Jacobson's work "dangerous" and Ken Caldeira emphasized that increasing hydropower output by 1,300 gigawatts, a 25% increase, is the equivalent flow of 100 Mississippi Rivers.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson published a response in the same issue of the *PNAS* and also authored a blog post where he asserted the researchers were advocates of the fossil fuel industry.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Another study published in 2017 confirmed the earlier results for a 100% renewable power system for North America, without changes in hydropower assumptions, but with more realistic emphasis on a balanced storage portfolio, in particular seasonal storage, and for competitive economics.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015, Jacobson and Delucchi, together with Mary Cameron and Bethany Frew, examined with computer simulation (Loadmatch), in more detail how a wind-water-solar (WWS) system can track the energy demand from minute to minute.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] This turned out to be possible in the United States for 6 years, including WWS variability by extreme weather events.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2017, the plan was further developed for 139 countries by a team of 27 researchers and in 2018, Jacobson and Delucchi with Mary Cameron and Brian Mathiesen published the Loadmatch results for 20 regions in which the 139 countries in the world are divided.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to this research, a WWS system can follow the demand in all regions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The program has been carried out for each region 10-20 times with adapted input for the storage capacities, until a solution was found in which the energy demand was followed, per half minute for 5 years, with low costs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2020, Jacobson clarified in a textbook computer simulation results of a WWS energy system.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] To match demand with supply every minute more solar and wind farms and high-voltage lines must be installed than to match year-averaged demand and supply.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] Oversizing (also in a conventional energy system) ensures that the demand can be followed during peak hours, but causes unused supply during off-peak hours.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a WWS system, more energy exchange between areas leads to more transmission loss.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The table shows WWS supply, unused supply, losses and end-use, in GW average power to reliably supply the world and four major regions with energy by 2050.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] See textbook Table 8.10; energy in TWh is divided by 26.3 kh (1000 hours) to get power in GW.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/100-renewable-energy-p02] The bottom row is the storage capacity of pumped hydro plants (Table 8.7).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] In 1996, a series of **radiotherapy accidents occurred in Costa Rica** within the *Alcyon II* radiotherapy unit at San Juan de Dios Hospital in San José, Costa Rica.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] It was related to a cobalt-60 source that was being used for radiotherapy in.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] An accidental overexposure of radiotherapy patients treated during August and September 1996 was detected.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] During the calibration process done after the change of 60Co source on 22 August 1996, a mistake was made in calculating the dose rate, leading to severe overexposure of patients.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] The error of calibration was detected on 27 September 1996, after which treatments ceased.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] It was determined that over the course of the accident, 115 patients received an overdose of radiation and of those, 13 died of confirmably radiation-related injuries.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] This number does not account for the many potential deaths, suicides, and uncontactable former patients that are believed to have had plausible stochastic connection to the overexposures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] The San Juan de Dios Hospital, located in Costa Rica, was one of the major medical facilities offering radiotherapy services in the country.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] In the mid-1990s, this facility introduced cobalt-60 therapy machines as a means of treating cancer.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] Radiotherapy is a critical component in cancer management; however, it requires careful calibration and dosimetry to ensure safety and efficacy in therapeutic procedures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] Prior to the accident in 1996, international concerns were growing over the dangers of radiation therapy errors, especially in poorly equipped facilities where outdated equipment and a lack of regulatory supervision could compromise safety.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] Costa Rica's health system was in the process of being upgraded at the time, and although radiotherapy was an established treatment modality, the strict application of safety measures and quality control procedures might not have been consistently practiced.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] Shortly after the incident, the Ministry of Health of Costa Rica conducted an evaluation which confirmed the overexposure to patients.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] It was found that during the calculation for the exposure time to patients, the wrong unit of time was used.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] The unit that the person in charge of dosimetry thought the machine was using was 1/100th of a minute, but the actual unit being used was seconds.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] This resulted in the dosage received by patients being approximately 60% higher than intended.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] It was not until July 1997 that an official review was carried out, and by that time, only 73 of the original patients remained alive.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] Of the 73, only 70 were examined and evaluated, and at the time of evaluation, 4 of the patients were suffering from "catastrophic consequences," while an additional 16 were experiencing major effects of overexposure.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] There were 26 individuals that were identified to be suffering minor effects but that in the future there was a higher risk of suffering further complications.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] 22 patients that were examined had little to no identifiable effects and were told they only had a low risk for future effects.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] 2 of the patients evaluated were underexposed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/1996-san-juan-de-dios-radiotherapy-accident] In 2001, the radiophysicist whose mistake caused the radiation overdoses was charged with 16 culpable homicides and sentenced to six years in prison.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 March 2011, at 14:46:24 JST (05:46:24 UTC), a Mw 9.0–9.1 undersea megathrust earthquake occurred in the Pacific Ocean, 72 km (45 mi) east of the Oshika Peninsula of the Tōhoku region of Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It lasted approximately six minutes and caused a tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is sometimes known in Japan as the "**Great East Japan Earthquake**" (東日本大震災, *Higashi Nihon Daishinsai*), among other names.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is often referred to by its numerical date, **3.11** (read *San ten Ichi-ichi* in Japanese).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was the most powerful ever recorded in Japan, and the fourth most powerful recorded in the world since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It triggered powerful tsunami waves that may have reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture, and which, in the Sendai area, traveled at 700 km/h (435 mph) and up to 10 km (6 mi) inland.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents of Sendai had only eight to ten minutes of warning, and more than a hundred evacuation sites were washed away.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The snowfall which accompanied the tsunami and the freezing temperature hindered rescue works; for instance, in Ishinomaki, the city with the most deaths, the temperature was 0 °C (32 °F) as the tsunami hit.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, 284 firefighters dead from attempts to close preventative fire gates, and 2,553 missing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report in 2015 found that 228,863 people were still living away from their home either temporarily or permanently.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami caused the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, primarily the meltdowns of three of its reactors, the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima and the associated evacuation zones affecting hundreds of thousands of residents.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Many electrical generators ran out of fuel.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The loss of electrical power halted cooling systems, causing heat to build.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Without ventilation, hydrogen gas accumulated within the upper refueling hall and exploded, forcefully ejecting the refueling hall's blast panels.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents within a 20 km (12 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant and a 10 km (6.2 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daini Nuclear Power Plant were evacuated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Early estimates placed insured losses from the earthquake alone at US$14.5 to $34.6 billion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Bank of Japan offered ¥15 trillion (US$183 billion) to the banking system on 14 March 2011 in an effort to normalize market conditions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The estimated economic damage amounted to over $300 billion, making it the costliest natural disaster in history.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a 2020 study, "the earthquake and its aftermaths resulted in a 0.47 percentage point decline in Japan's real GDP growth in the year following the disaster".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was initially reported as 7.9 Mw by the USGS before it was quickly upgraded to 8.8 Mw, then to 8.9 Mw, and then finally to 9.0 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 July 2016, the USGS further upgraded the earthquake to 9.1.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Sendai was the nearest major city to the earthquake, 130 km (81 mi) from the epicenter; the earthquake occurred 373 km (232 mi) northeast of Tokyo.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main earthquake was preceded by a number of large foreshocks, with hundreds of aftershocks reported.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One of the first major foreshocks was a 7.2 Mw event on 9 March, approximately 40 km (25 mi) from the epicenter of the 11 March earthquake, with another three on the same day in excess of 6.0 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the main earthquake on 11 March, a 7.4 Mw aftershock was reported at 15:08 JST (6:06 UTC), succeeded by a 7.9 Mw at 15:15 JST (6:16 UTC) and a 7.7 Mw at 15:26 JST (6:26 UTC).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Over 800 aftershocks of magnitude 4.5 Mw or greater occurred after the initial quake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Aftershocks followed Omori's law, which states that the rate of aftershocks declines with the reciprocal of the time since the main quake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The aftershocks thus tapered off over time, but continued for years after the initial quake, including one on 26 October 2013 (local time) of magnitude 7.1 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Initially, the earthquake caused part of Honshu's Pacific coast to sink by roughly a meter, but after about three years, the coast rose back and then kept on rising to exceed its original height.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This megathrust earthquake was a recurrence of the mechanism of the earlier 869 Sanriku earthquake, which has been estimated as having a magnitude of at least 8.4 Mw, which also created a large tsunami that inundated the Sendai plain.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three tsunami deposits have been identified within the Holocene sequence of the plain, all formed within the last 3,000 years, suggesting an 800 to 1,100 year recurrence interval for large tsunamigenic earthquakes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2001 it was reckoned that there was a high likelihood of a large tsunami hitting the Sendai plain as more than 1,100 years had then elapsed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2007, the probability of an earthquake with a magnitude of Mw 8.1–8.3 was estimated as 99% within the following 30 years.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This earthquake occurred where the Pacific plate is subducting under the plate beneath northern Honshu.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific plate, which moves at a rate of 8 to 9 cm (3.1 to 3.5 in) per year, dips under Honshu's underlying plate, building large amounts of elastic energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motion pushes the upper plate down until the accumulated stress causes a seismic slip-rupture event.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The break caused the sea floor to rise by several meters.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The magnitude of this earthquake was a surprise to some seismologists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A quake of this magnitude usually has a rupture length of at least 500 km (310 mi) and generally requires a long, relatively straight fault surface.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because the plate boundary and subduction zone in the area of the Honshu rupture is not very straight, it is unusual for the magnitude of its earthquake to exceed 8.5 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The hypocentral region of this earthquake extended from offshore Iwate Prefecture to offshore Ibaraki Prefecture.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency said that the earthquake may have ruptured the fault zone from Iwate to Ibaraki with a length of 500 km (310 mi) and a width of 200 km (120 mi).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Analysis showed that this earthquake consisted of a set of three events.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other major earthquakes with tsunamis struck the Sanriku Coast region in 1896 and in 1933.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The source area of this earthquake has a relatively high coupling coefficient surrounded by areas of relatively low coupling coefficients in the west, north, and south.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment of this earthquake accounts for about 93% of the estimated cumulative moment from 1926 to March 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hence, earthquakes in this area with magnitudes of about 7 since 1926 had only released part of the accumulated energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the area near the trench, the coupling coefficient is high, which could act as the source of the large tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Most of the foreshocks are interplate earthquakes with thrust-type focal mechanisms.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Both interplate and intraplate earthquakes appeared in the aftershocks offshore Sanriku coast with considerable proportions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surface energy of the seismic waves from the earthquake was calculated to be 1.9×1017 joules, which is nearly double that of the 9.1 Mw 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami that killed 230,000 people.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] If harnessed, the seismic energy from this earthquake would power a city the size of Los Angeles for an entire year.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment (M0), which represents a physical size for the event, was calculated by the USGS at 3.9×1022 joules, slightly less than the 2004 Indian Ocean quake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The strong ground motion registered at the maximum of *Shindo* 7 on the Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale in Kurihara, Miyagi Prefecture.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three other prefectures—Fukushima, Ibaraki and Tochigi—recorded a 6 upper on the JMA scale.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seismic stations in Iwate, Gunma, Saitama and Chiba Prefectures measured a 6 lower, while Tokyo and five other prefectures recorded 5 upper.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan's National Research Institute for Earth Science and Disaster Prevention (NIED) calculated a peak ground acceleration of 2.99 *g* (29.33 m/s2).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Tremors from the earthquake were also felt in the Northern Mariana Islands, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan, Northeast China and the Russian Far East.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Portions of northeastern Japan shifted by as much as 2.4 meters (7 ft 10 in) closer to North America, making some sections of Japan's landmass wider than before.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Those areas of Japan closest to the epicenter experienced the largest shifts.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 400-kilometer (250 mi) stretch of coastline dropped vertically by 0.6 meters (2 ft 0 in), allowing the tsunami to travel farther and faster onto land.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One early estimate suggested that the Pacific plate may have moved westward by up to 20 meters (66 ft), and another early estimate put the amount of slippage at as much as 40 m (130 ft).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 6 April, the Japanese coast guard said that the quake shifted the seabed near the epicenter 24 meters (79 ft) and elevated the seabed off the coast of Miyagi Prefecture by 3 meters (9.8 ft).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report by the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, published in *Science* on 2 December 2011, concluded that the seabed in the area between the epicenter and the Japan Trench moved 50 meters (160 ft) east-southeast and rose about 7 meters (23 ft) as a result of the quake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The report also stated that the quake had caused several major landslides on the seabed in the affected area.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Earth's axis shifted by estimates of between 10 and 25 cm (4 and 10 in).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This deviation led to a number of small planetary changes, including the length of a day, the tilt of the Earth, and the Chandler wobble.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The speed of the Earth's rotation increased, shortening the day by 1.8 microseconds due to the redistribution of Earth's mass.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The axial shift was caused by the redistribution of mass on the Earth's surface, which changed the planet's moment of inertia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because of conservation of angular momentum, such changes of inertia result in small changes to the Earth's rate of rotation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These are expected changes for an earthquake of this magnitude.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake also generated infrasound waves detected by perturbations in the orbit of the GOCE satellite, which thus serendipitously became the first seismograph in orbit.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the earthquake, cracks were observed to have formed in the roof of Mount Fuji's magma chamber.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seiches observed in Sognefjorden, Norway, were attributed to distant S waves and Love waves generated by the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These seiches began to occur roughly half an hour after the main shock hit Japan, and continued to occur for 3 hours, during which waves of up to 1.5 meters high were observed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Soil liquefaction was evident in areas of reclaimed land around Tokyo, particularly in Urayasu, Chiba City, Funabashi, Narashino (all in Chiba Prefecture) and in the Koto, Edogawa, Minato, Chūō, and Ōta wards of Tokyo.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Approximately 30 homes or buildings were destroyed and 1,046 other buildings were damaged to varying degrees.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Nearby Haneda Airport, built mostly on reclaimed land, was not damaged.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Odaiba also experienced liquefaction, but damage was minimal.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Shinmoedake, a volcano in Kyushu, erupted three days after the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The volcano had previously erupted in January 2011; it is not known if the later eruption was linked to the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Antarctica, the seismic waves from the earthquake were reported to have caused the Whillans Ice Stream to slip by about 0.5 meters (1 ft 8 in).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The first sign international researchers had that the earthquake caused such a dramatic change in the Earth's rotation came from the United States Geological Survey which monitors Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) stations across the world.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Survey team had several GPS monitors located near the scene of the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The GPS station located nearest the epicenter moved almost 4 m (13 ft).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motivated government researchers to look into other ways the earthquake may have had large scale effects on the planet.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Calculations at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory determined that the Earth's rotation was changed by the earthquake to the point where the days are now 1.8 microseconds shorter.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan experienced over 1,000 aftershocks since the earthquake, with 80 registering over magnitude 6.0 Mw and several of which have been over magnitude 7.0 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A month later, a major aftershock struck offshore on 7 April with a magnitude of 7.1 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Its epicenter was underwater, 66 km (41 mi) off the coast of Sendai.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency assigned a magnitude of 7.4 MJMA, while the United States Geological Survey lowered it to 7.1 Mw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least four people were killed, and electricity was cut off across much of northern Japan including the loss of external power to Higashidōri Nuclear Power Plant and Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Four days later on 11 April, another magnitude 7.1 Mw aftershock struck Fukushima, causing additional damage and killing a total of three people.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 7 December 2012 a large aftershock of magnitude 7.3 Mw caused a minor tsunami, and again on 26 October 2013 a small tsunami was recorded after a 7.1 Mw aftershock.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 16 March 2012 aftershocks continued, totaling 1887 events over magnitude 4.0; a regularly updated map showing all shocks of magnitude 4.5 and above near or off the east coast of Honshu in the last seven days showed over 20 events.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 11 March 2016 there had been 869 aftershocks of 5.0 Mw or greater, 118 of 6.0 Mw or greater, and 9 over 7.0 Mw as reported by the Japan Meteorological Agency.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The number of aftershocks was associated with decreased health across Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 February 2021, a magnitude 7.1–7.3 earthquake struck off the coast of Sendai.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It caused some damage in Miyagi and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One person was killed, and 185 were injured.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Geospatial Information Authority of Japan reported land subsidence based on the height of triangulation stations in the area measured by GPS as compared to their previous values from 14 April 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Scientists say that the subsidence is permanent.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As a result, the communities in question are now more susceptible to flooding during high tides.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One minute before the earthquake was felt in Tokyo, the Earthquake Early Warning system, which includes more than 1,000 seismometers in Japan, sent out warnings of impending strong shaking to millions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is believed that the early warning by the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) saved many lives.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning for the general public was delivered about eight seconds after the first P wave was detected, or about 31 seconds after the earthquake occurred.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the estimated intensities were smaller than the actual ones in some places, especially in Kanto, Koshinetsu, and Northern Tōhoku regions where the populace warning did not trigger.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There were also cases where large differences between estimated intensities by the Earthquake Early Warning system and the actual intensities occurred in the aftershocks and triggered earthquakes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Such discrepancies in the warning were attributed by the JMA to the system's inability to distinguish between two different earthquakes that happened at around same time, as well as to the reduced number of reporting seismometers due to power outages and connection failures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The system's software was subsequently modified to handle this kind of situation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] An upthrust of 6 to 8 meters (20 to 26 ft) along a 180-kilometer (110 mi)-wide seabed at 60 kilometers (37 mi) offshore from the east coast of Tōhoku resulted in a major tsunami that brought destruction along the Pacific coastline of Japan's northern islands.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Thousands of people died and entire towns were devastated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami propagated throughout the Pacific Ocean region reaching the entire Pacific coast of North and South America from Alaska to Chile.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Warnings were issued and evacuations were carried out in many countries bordering the Pacific.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Although the tsunami affected many of these places, the heights of the waves were minor.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Chile's Pacific coast, one of the farthest from Japan at about 17,000 kilometers (11,000 mi) away, was struck by waves 2 meters (6.6 ft) high, compared with an estimated wave height of 38.9 meters (128 ft) at Omoe peninsula, Miyako city, Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami warning issued by the Japan Meteorological Agency was the most serious on its warning scale; it was rated as a "major tsunami", being at least 3 meters (9.8 ft) high.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The actual height prediction varied, the greatest being for Miyagi at 6 meters (20 ft) high.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami inundated a total area of approximately 561 square kilometers (217 sq mi) in Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 15:55 JST, a tsunami was observed flooding Sendai Airport, which is located near the coast of Miyagi Prefecture, with waves sweeping away cars and planes and flooding various buildings as they traveled inland.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The impact of the tsunami in and around Sendai Airport was filmed by an NHK News helicopter, showing a number of vehicles on local roads trying to escape the approaching wave and being engulfed by it.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 4-meter-high (13 ft) tsunami hit Iwate Prefecture.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Wakabayashi Ward in Sendai was also particularly hard hit.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least 101 designated tsunami evacuation sites were hit by the wave.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Like the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, the damage by surging water, though much more localized, was far more deadly and destructive than the actual quake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Entire towns were destroyed in tsunami-hit areas in Japan, including 9,500 missing in Minamisanriku; one thousand bodies had been recovered in the town by 14 March 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Among the factors in the high death toll was the unexpectedly large water surge.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The sea walls in several cities had been built to protect against tsunamis of much lower heights.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, many people caught in the tsunami thought they were on high enough ground to be safe.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a special committee on disaster prevention designated by the Japanese government, the tsunami protection policy had been intended to deal with only tsunamis that had been scientifically proved to occur repeatedly.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The committee advised that future policy should be to protect against the highest possible tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because tsunami walls had been overtopped, the committee also suggested, besides building taller tsunami walls, also teaching citizens how to evacuate if a large-scale tsunami should strike.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Large parts of Kuji and the southern section of Ōfunato including the port area were almost entirely destroyed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also largely destroyed was Rikuzentakata, where the tsunami was three stories high.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other cities destroyed or heavily damaged by the tsunami include Kamaishi, Miyako, Ōtsuchi, and Yamada (in Iwate Prefecture), Namie, Sōma, and Minamisōma (in Fukushima Prefecture) and Shichigahama, Higashimatsushima, Onagawa, Natori, Ishinomaki, and Kesennuma (in Miyagi Prefecture).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The most severe effects of the tsunami were felt along a 670-kilometer-long (420 mi) stretch of coastline from Erimo, Hokkaido, in the north to Ōarai, Ibaraki, in the south, with most of the destruction in that area occurring in the hour following the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Near Ōarai, people captured images of a huge whirlpool that had been generated by the tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami washed away the sole bridge to Miyatojima, Miyagi, isolating the island's 900 residents.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2 meters (6 ft 7 in) high tsunami hit Chiba Prefecture about 2+1⁄2 hours after the quake, causing heavy damage to cities such as Asahi.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 March 2011, the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) published details of tsunami observations recorded around the coastline of Japan following the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The bulletin also included initial tsunami observation details, as well as more detailed maps for the coastlines affected by the tsunami waves.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami at Ryōri Bay (綾里湾), Ōfunato reached a height of 40.1 meters (132 ft) (run-up elevation).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Fishing equipment was scattered on the high cliff above the bay.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At Tarō, Iwate, the tsunami reached a height of 37.9 meters (124 ft) up the slope of a mountain some 200 meters (660 ft) away from the coastline.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, at the slope of a nearby mountain from 400 meters (1,300 ft) away at Aneyoshi fishery port (姉吉漁港) of Omoe peninsula (重茂半島) in Miyako, Iwate, Tokyo University of Marine Science and Technology found estimated tsunami run up height of 38.9 meters (128 ft).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This height is deemed the record in Japan historically, as of reporting date, that exceeds 38.2 meters (125 ft) from the 1896 Sanriku earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was also estimated that the tsunami reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The inundated areas closely matched those of the 869 Sanriku tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Inundation heights were observed along 2,000 kilometers (1,200 mi) of the coast from Hokkaido to Kyushu in a 2012 study.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Maximum run-up heights greater than 10 meters (33 ft) were distributed along 530 kilometers (330 mi) of coast, and maximum run-up heights greater than 20 meters (66 ft) were distributed along 200 kilometers (120 mi) of the coast, measured directly.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami resulted in significant erosion of the Rikuzen-Takata coastline, mainly caused by backwash.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2016 study indicated that the coast has not naturally recovered at a desirable rate since the tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A Japanese government study found that 58% of people in coastal areas in Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures heeded tsunami warnings immediately after the quake and headed for higher ground.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who attempted to evacuate after hearing the warning, only five percent were caught in the tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who did not heed the warning, 49% were hit by the water.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Delayed evacuations in response to the warnings had a number of causes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami height that had been initially predicted by the tsunami warning system was lower than the actual tsunami height; this error contributed to the delayed escape of some residents.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The discrepancy arose as follows: in order to produce a quick prediction of a tsunami's height and thus to provide a timely warning, the initial earthquake and tsunami warning that was issued for the event was based on a calculation that requires only about three minutes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This calculation is, in turn, based on the maximum amplitude of the seismic wave.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The amplitude of the seismic wave is measured using the JMA magnitude scale, which is similar to Richter scale.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, these scales "saturate" for earthquakes that are above a certain magnitude (magnitude 8 on the JMA scale); that is, in the case of very large earthquakes, the scales' values change little despite large differences in the earthquakes' energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This resulted in an underestimation of the tsunami's height in initial reports.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Problems in issuing updates also contributed to delays in evacuations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning system was supposed to be updated about 15 minutes after the earthquake occurred, by which time the calculation for the moment magnitude scale would normally be completed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the strong quake had exceeded the measurement limit of all of the teleseismometers within Japan, and thus it was impossible to calculate the moment magnitude based on data from those seismometers.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Another cause of delayed evacuations was the release of the second update on the tsunami warning long after the earthquake (28 minutes, according to observations); by that time, power failures and similar circumstances reportedly prevented the update from reaching some residents.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, observed data from tidal meters that were located off the coast were not fully reflected in the second warning.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In response to the aforementioned shortcomings in the tsunami warning system, JMA began an investigation in 2011 and updated their system in 2013.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the updated system, for a powerful earthquake that is capable of causing the JMA magnitude scale to saturate, no quantitative prediction will be released in the initial warning; instead, there will be words that describe the situation's emergency.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There are plans to install new teleseismometers with the ability to measure larger earthquakes, which would allow the calculation of a quake's moment magnitude scale in a timely manner.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] JMA also implemented a simpler empirical method to integrate, into a tsunami warning, data from GPS tidal meters as well as from undersea water pressure meters, and there are plans to install more of these meters and to develop further technology to utilize data observed by them.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] To prevent under-reporting of tsunami heights, early quantitative observation data that are smaller than the expected amplitude will be overridden and the public will instead be told that the situation is under observation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] About 90 seconds after an earthquake, an additional report on the possibility of a tsunami will also be included in observation reports, in order to warn people before the JMA magnitude can be calculated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center (PTWC) in Hawaii issued tsunami watches and announcements for locations in the Pacific.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 07:30 UTC, PTWC issued a widespread tsunami warning covering the entire Pacific Ocean.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Russia evacuated 11,000 residents from coastal areas of the Kuril Islands.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The United States National Tsunami Warning Center issued a tsunami warning for the coastal areas in most of California, all of Oregon, and the western part of Alaska, and a tsunami advisory covering the Pacific coastlines of most of Alaska, and all of Washington and British Columbia, Canada.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In California and Oregon, up to 2.4 m-high (7.9 ft) tsunami waves hit some areas, damaging docks and harbors and causing over US$10 million in damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Curry County, Oregon, US$7 million in damage occurred including the destruction of 1,100 m (3,600 ft) of docks at the Brookings harbor; the county received over US$1 million in FEMA emergency grants from the US Federal Government.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Surges of up to 1 m (3 ft 3 in) hit Vancouver Island in Canada prompting some evacuations, and causing boats to be banned from the waters surrounding the island for 12 hours following the wave strike, leaving many island residents in the area without means of getting to work.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Philippines, waves up to 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) high hit the eastern seaboard of the country.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some houses along the coast in Jayapura, Indonesia were destroyed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Authorities in Wewak, East Sepik, Papua New Guinea evacuated 100 patients from the city's Boram Hospital before it was hit by waves, causing an estimated US$4 million in damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hawaii estimated damage to public infrastructure alone at US$3 million, with damage to private properties, including resort hotels such as Four Seasons Resort Hualalai, estimated at tens of millions of dollars.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was reported that a 1.5 m-high (4.9 ft) wave completely submerged Midway Atoll's reef inlets and Spit Island, killing more than 110,000 nesting seabirds at the Midway Atoll National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some other South Pacific countries, including Tonga and New Zealand, and US territories American Samoa and Guam, experienced larger-than-normal waves, but did not report any major damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, in Guam some roads were closed off and people were evacuated from low-lying areas.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Along the Pacific Coast of Mexico and South America, tsunami surges were reported, but in most places caused little or no damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Peru reported a wave of 1.5 m (4 ft 11 in) and more than 300 homes damaged.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surge in Chile was large enough to damage more than 200 houses, with waves of up to 3 m (9.8 ft).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Galápagos Islands, 260 families received assistance following a 3 m (9.8 ft) surge which arrived 20 hours after the earthquake, after the tsunami warning had been lifted.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There was a great deal of damage to buildings on the islands and one man was injured but there were no reported fatalities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami broke icebergs off the Sulzberger Ice Shelf in Antarctica, 13,000 km (8,100 mi) away.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main iceberg measured 9.5 km × 6.5 km (5.9 mi × 4.0 mi) (approximately the area of Manhattan Island) and about 80 m (260 ft) thick.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A total of 125 km2 (48 sq mi; 31,000 acres) of ice broke away.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of April 2012, wreckage from the tsunami spread around the world, including a soccer ball which was found in Alaska's Middleton Island and a Japanese motorcycle found in British Columbia, Canada.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On the day of the earthquake, the waters of several fjords across Norway appeared to seethe as if boiling, and formed waves that rolled onto shores, most prominently in Sognefjorden, where the phenomenon was caught on film.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] After two years of research into the incidents in Norway, scientists concluded that the seismic energy of the earthquake generated seiche waves thousands of kilometers away.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, and 2,553 missing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were 10,567 deaths in Miyagi, 5,145 in Iwate, 3,920 in Fukushima, 66 in Ibaraki, 22 in Chiba, eight in Tokyo, six in Kanagawa, four in Tochigi, three each in Aomori and Yamagata, and one each in Gunma, Saitama and Hokkaido.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The leading causes of death were drowning (90.64% or 14,308 bodies), burning (0.9% or 145 bodies) and others (4.2% or 667 bodies, mostly crushed by heavy objects).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Injuries related to nuclear exposure or the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima are difficult to trace as 60% of the 20,000 workers on-site declined to participate in state-sponsored free health checks.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Elderly aged over 60 account for 65.8% of all deaths, as shown on the table to the right.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A few cases of suicide are also included.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred during the first six months after the earthquake and the number dropped thereafter, but as time has passed, the number has continued to increase.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred in Fukushima Prefecture, where the prefectural government has suggested that they could be due to evacuations caused by the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Fukushima Prefecture, these indirect casualties have already resulted in more deaths than the number of people killed directly by earthquake and tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Save the Children reports that as many as 100,000 children were uprooted from their homes, some of whom were separated from their families because the earthquake occurred during the school day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 236 children were orphaned in the prefectures of Iwate, Miyagi and Fukushima by the disaster; 1,580 children lost either one or both parents, 846 in Miyagi, 572 in Iwate, and 162 in Fukushima.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The quake and tsunami killed 378 elementary, middle-school, and high school students and left 158 others missing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One elementary school in Ishinomaki, Miyagi, Okawa Elementary School, lost 74 of 108 students and 10 of 13 teachers in the tsunami due to poor decision making in evacuation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Japanese Foreign Ministry confirmed the deaths of nineteen foreigners.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Among them were two English teachers from the United States affiliated with the Japan Exchange and Teaching Program; a Canadian missionary in Shiogama; and citizens of China, North and South Korea, Taiwan, Pakistan and the Philippines.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 9:30 UTC on 11 March 2011, Google Person Finder, which was previously used in the Haitian, Chilean, and Christchurch, New Zealand earthquakes, was collecting information about survivors and their locations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese funerals are normally elaborate Buddhist ceremonies that entail cremation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The thousands of bodies, however, exceeded the capacity of available crematoriums and morgues, many of them damaged, and there were shortages of both kerosene—each cremation requires 50 litres—and dry ice for preservation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The single crematorium in Higashimatsushima, for example, could only handle four bodies a day, although hundreds were found there.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Governments and the military were forced to bury many bodies in hastily dug mass graves with rudimentary or no rites, although relatives of the deceased were promised that they would be cremated later.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 27 May 2011, three Japan Ground Self-Defense Force members had died while conducting relief operations in Tōhoku.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of March 2012, the Japanese government had recognized 1,331 deaths as indirectly related to the earthquake, such as caused by harsh living conditions after the disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 30 April 2012, 18 people had died and 420 had been injured while participating in disaster recovery or clean-up efforts.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami was reported to have caused several deaths outside Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One man was killed in Jayapura, Papua, Indonesia after being swept out to sea.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A man who is said to have been attempting to photograph the oncoming tsunami at the mouth of the Klamath River, south of Crescent City, California, was swept out to sea.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] His body was found on 2 April 2011 along Ocean Beach in Fort Stevens State Park, Oregon, 530 km (330 mi) to the north.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The degree and extent of damage caused by the earthquake and resulting tsunami were enormous, with most of the damage being caused by the tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Video footage of the towns that were worst affected shows little more than piles of rubble, with almost no parts of any structures left standing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Estimates of the cost of the damage range well into the tens of billions of US dollars; before-and-after satellite photographs of devastated regions show immense damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Although Japan has invested the equivalent of billions of dollars on anti-tsunami seawalls which line at least 40% of its 34,751 km (21,593 mi) coastline and stand up to 12 m (39 ft) high, the tsunami simply washed over the top of some seawalls, collapsing some in the process.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's National Police Agency said on 3 April 2011, that 45,700 buildings were destroyed and 144,300 were damaged by the quake and tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The damaged buildings included 29,500 structures in Miyagi Prefecture, 12,500 in Iwate Prefecture and 2,400 in Fukushima Prefecture.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Three hundred hospitals with 20 beds or more in Tōhoku were damaged by the disaster, with 11 being completely destroyed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami created an estimated 24–25 million tons of rubble and debris in Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the National Police Agency of Japan on 10 September 2018 listed 121,778 buildings as "total collapsed", with a further 280,926 buildings "half collapsed", and another 699,180 buildings "partially damaged".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami also caused extensive and severe structural damage in north-eastern Japan, including heavy damage to roads and railways as well as fires in many areas, and a dam collapse.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese Prime Minister Naoto Kan said, "In the 65 years after the end of World War II, this is the toughest and the most difficult crisis for Japan." Around 4.4 million households in northeastern Japan were left without electricity and 1.5 million without water.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An estimated 230,000 automobiles and trucks were damaged or destroyed in the disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of the end of May 2011, residents of Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures had requested the deregistration of 15,000 vehicles, meaning that the owners of those vehicles were writing them off as unrepairable or unsalvageable.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Low temperature and snowfall were major concerns after the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Snow arrived minutes before or after the tsunami, depending on locations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki, the city which suffered the most deaths, a temperature of 0 °C (32 °F) was measured, and it began to snow within a couple of hours of the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major snow fell again on 16 March, and intermittently in the coming weeks.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 18 March was the coldest of that month, recording −4 to 6 °C (25 to 43 °F) in Sendai.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Photos of city ruins covered with snow were featured in various photo albums in international media, including NASA.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami produced huge amounts of debris: estimates of 5 million tonnes of waste were reported by the Japanese Ministry of the Environment.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Some of this waste, mostly plastic and styrofoam, washed up on the coasts of Canada and the United States in late 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Along the west coast of the United States, this increased the amount of litter by a factor of ten and may have transported alien species.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All of Japan's ports were briefly shut down after the earthquake, though the ones in Tokyo and southwards soon re-opened.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Fifteen ports were located in the disaster zone.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The north eastern ports of Hachinohe, Sendai, Ishinomaki and Onahama were destroyed, while the Port of Chiba (which serves the hydrocarbon industry) and Japan's ninth-largest container port at Kashima were also affected, though less severely.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The ports at Hitachinaka, Hitachi, Soma, Shiogama, Kesennuma, Ofunato, Kamashi and Miyako were also damaged and closed to ships.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All 15 ports reopened to limited ship traffic by 29 March 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A total of 319 fishing ports, about 10% of Japan's fishing ports, were damaged in the disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most were restored to operating condition by 18 April 2012.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Port of Tokyo suffered slight damage; the effects of the quake included visible smoke rising from a building in the port with parts of the port areas being flooded, including soil liquefaction in Tokyo Disneyland's parking lot.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fujinuma irrigation dam in Sukagawa ruptured, causing flooding and the washing away of five homes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eight people were missing and four bodies were discovered by the morning.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Reportedly, some locals had attempted to repair leaks in the dam before it completely failed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 12 March 252 dams were inspected and it was discovered that six embankment dams had shallow cracks on their crests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reservoir at one concrete gravity dam suffered a small non-serious slope failure.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All damaged dams are functioning with no problems.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four dams within the quake area were unreachable.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the immediate aftermath of the calamity, at least 1.5 million households were reported to have lost access to water supplies.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, this number fell to 1.04 million.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to the Japanese trade ministry, around 4.4 million households served by Tōhoku Electric Power (TEP) in northeastern Japan were left without electricity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Several nuclear and conventional power plants went offline, reducing the Tokyo Electric Power Company's (TEPCO) total capacity by 21 GW.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts began on 14 March due to power shortages caused by the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] TEPCO, which normally provides approximately 40 GW of electricity, announced that it could only provide about 30 GW, because 40% of the electricity used in the greater Tokyo area was supplied by reactors in the Niigata and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reactors at the Fukushima Daiichi and Fukushima Dai-ni plants were automatically taken offline when the first earthquake occurred and sustained major damage from the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts of approximately three hours were experienced throughout April and May while TEPCO scrambled to find a temporary power solution.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blackouts affected Tokyo, Kanagawa, Eastern Shizuoka, Yamanashi, Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, Tochigi, and Gunma prefectures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Voluntary reductions in electricity use by consumers in the Kanto area helped reduce the predicted frequency and duration of the blackouts.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, the number of households in the north without electricity fell to 242,927.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power was not able to provide the Kanto region with additional power because TEP's power plants were also damaged in the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Two substations, one in Shizuoka Prefecture and one in Nagano Prefecture, were able to convert between frequencies and transfer electricity from Kansai to Kanto and Tōhoku, but their capacity was limited to 1 GW.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] With damage to so many power plants, it was feared it might be years before a long-term solution could be found.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To help alleviate the shortage, three steel manufacturers in the Kanto region contributed electricity produced by their in-house conventional power stations to TEPCO for distribution to the general public.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Sumitomo Metal Industries could produce up to 500 MW, JFE Steel 400 MW, and Nippon Steel 500 MW of electric power.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Auto and auto parts makers in Kanto and Tōhoku agreed in May 2011 to operate their factories on Saturdays and Sundays and close on Thursdays and Fridays to help alleviate electricity shortages during the summer of 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The public and other companies were also encouraged to conserve electricity in the 2011 summer months (Setsuden).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expected electricity crisis in 2011 summer was successfully prevented thanks to all the *setsuden* measures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Peak electricity consumption recorded by TEPCO during the period was 49.22GW, which is 10.77GW (18%) lower than the peak consumption in the previous year.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Overall electricity consumption during July and August was also 14% less than in the previous year.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The peak electricity consumption within TEP's area was 12.46GW during the 2011 summer, 3.11GW (20%) less than the peak consumption in the previous year, and the overall consumption have been reduced by 11% in July with 17% in August compared to previous year.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A 220,000-barrel-per-day (35,000 m3) oil refinery of Cosmo Oil Company was set on fire by the quake at Ichihara, Chiba Prefecture, to the east of Tokyo.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It was extinguished after ten days, injuring six people, and destroying storage tanks.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other refineries halted production due to safety checks and power loss.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Sendai, a 145,000-barrel-per-day (23,100 m3) refinery owned by the largest refiner in Japan, JX Nippon Oil & Energy, was also set ablaze by the quake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Workers were evacuated, but tsunami warnings hindered efforts to extinguish the fire until 14 March, when officials planned to do so.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An analyst estimated that consumption of various types of oil could have increased by as much as 300,000 barrels (48,000 m3) per day (as well as LNG), as back-up power plants burning fossil fuels attempted to compensate for the loss of 11 GW of Japan's nuclear power capacity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The city-owned plant for importing liquefied natural gas in Sendai was severely damaged, and supplies were halted for at least a month.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In addition to refining and storage, several power plants were damaged.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] These include Sendai #4, New-Sendai #1 and #2, Haranomachi #1 and #2, Hirono #2 and #4 and Hitachinaka #1.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fukushima Daiichi, Fukushima Daini, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant and Tōkai nuclear power stations, consisting of a total eleven reactors, were automatically shut down following the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Higashidōri, also on the northeast coast, was already shut down for a periodic inspection.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cooling is needed to remove decay heat after a Generation II reactor has been shut down, and to maintain spent fuel pools.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The backup cooling process is powered by emergency diesel generators at the plants and at Rokkasho nuclear reprocessing plant.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Fukushima Daiichi and Daini, tsunami waves overtopped seawalls and destroyed diesel backup power systems, leading to severe problems at Fukushima Daiichi, including three large explosions and radioactive leakage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Subsequent analysis found that many Japanese nuclear plants, including Fukushima Daiichi, were not adequately protected against tsunamis.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima was confirmed in later analysis at the three reactors at Fukushima I (Units 1, 2, and 3), which suffered meltdowns and continued to leak coolant water.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftershock on 7 April caused the loss of external power to Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant and Higashidori Nuclear Power Plant but backup generators were functional.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of its four external power lines and temporarily lost cooling function in its spent fuel pools for "20 to 80 minutes".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of "up to 3.8 litres [1.0 US gal]" of radioactive water also occurred at Onagawa following the aftershock.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the IAEA in 2012 found that the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant had remained largely undamaged.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2013, only two nuclear reactors in Japan had been restarted since the 2011 shutdowns.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2019, there were 42 operable reactors in Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Of these, only nine reactors in five power plants were operating after having been restarted post-2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan declared a state of emergency following the failure of the cooling system at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, resulting in the evacuation of nearby residents.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Officials from the Japanese Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency reported that radiation levels inside the plant were up to 1,000 times normal levels, and that radiation levels outside the plant were up to eight times normal levels.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Later, a state of emergency was also declared at the Fukushima Daini nuclear power plant about 11 km (6.8 mi) south.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Experts described the Fukushima disaster was not as bad as the Chernobyl disaster, but worse than the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant was later detected in tap water.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive iodine was detected in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi, Gunma, Tokyo, Chiba, Saitama, and Niigata, and radioactive caesium in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi and Gunma.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive caesium, iodine, and strontium were also detected in the soil in some places in Fukushima.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There may be a need to replace the contaminated soil.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many radioactive hotspots were found outside the evacuation zone, including Tokyo.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive contamination of food products were detected in several places in Japan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2021, the Japanese cabinet finally approved the dumping of radioactive water in Fukushima into the Pacific Ocean over a course of 30 years, with full support of IAEA.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To this day, the water is still actively being de-contaminated and is scheduled to be completed by the year 2051.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A fire occurred in the turbine section of the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant following the earthquake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blaze was in a building housing the turbine, which is sited separately from the plant's reactor, and was soon extinguished.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The plant was shut down as a precaution.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 13 March the lowest-level state of emergency was declared regarding the Onagawa plant as radioactivity readings temporarily exceeded allowed levels in the area of the plant.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power Co. stated this may have been due to radiation from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear accidents but was not from the Onagawa plant itself.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As a result of the 7 April aftershock, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of four external power lines and lost cooling function for as much as 80 minutes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of a couple of litres of radioactive water occurred at Onagawa.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The number 2 reactor at Tōkai Nuclear Power Plant was shut down automatically.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's transport network suffered severe disruptions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many sections of Tōhoku Expressway serving northern Japan were damaged.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expressway did not reopen to general public use until 24 March 2011.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All railway services were suspended in Tokyo, with an estimated 20,000 people stranded at major stations across the city.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the hours after the earthquake, some train services were resumed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most Tokyo area train lines resumed full service by the next day—12 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twenty thousand stranded visitors spent the night of 11–12 March inside Tokyo Disneyland.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A tsunami flooded Sendai Airport at 15:55 JST, about one hour after the initial quake, causing severe damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Narita and Haneda Airport both briefly suspended operations after the quake, but suffered little damage and reopened within 24 hours.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eleven airliners bound for Narita were diverted to nearby Yokota Air Base.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Various train services around Japan were also canceled, with JR East suspending all services for the rest of the day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four trains on coastal lines were reported as being out of contact with operators; one, a four-car train on the Senseki Line, was found to have derailed, and its occupants were rescued shortly after 8 am the next morning.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were no derailments of Shinkansen bullet train services in and out of Tokyo, but their services were also suspended.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tokaido Shinkansen resumed limited service late in the day and was back to its normal schedule by the next day, while the Jōetsu and Nagano Shinkansen resumed services late on 12 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Yamagata Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 31 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Derailments were minimized because of an early warning system that detected the earthquake before it struck.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The system automatically stopped all high-speed trains, which minimized the damage.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tōhoku Shinkansen line was worst hit, with JR East estimating that 1,100 sections of the line, varying from collapsed station roofs to bent power pylons, would need repairs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on the Tōhoku Shinkansen partially resumed only in Kantō area on 15 March, with one round-trip service per hour between Tokyo and Nasu-Shiobara, and Tōhoku area service partially resumed on 22 March between Morioka and Shin-Aomori.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Akita Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 18 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Service between Tokyo and Shin-Aomori was restored by May, but at lower speeds due to ongoing restoration work; the pre-earthquake timetable was not reinstated until late September.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The rolling blackouts brought on by the crises at the nuclear power plants in Fukushima had a profound effect on the rail networks around Tokyo starting on 14 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major railways began running trains at 10–20 minute intervals, rather than the usual 3–5 minute intervals, operating some lines only at rush hour and completely shutting down others; notably, the Tōkaidō Main Line, Yokosuka Line, Sōbu Main Line and Chūō-Sōbu Line were all stopped for the day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This led to near-paralysis within the capital, with long lines at train stations and many people unable to come to work or get home.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Railway operators gradually increased capacity over the next few days, until running at approximately 80% capacity by 17 March and relieving the worst of the passenger congestion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] (left) and a damaged utility pole in Ishinomaki (right).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cellular and landline phone service suffered major disruptions in the affected area.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Immediately after the earthquake cellular communication was jammed across much of Japan due to a surge of network activity.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On the day of the quake itself American broadcaster NPR was unable to reach anyone in Sendai with a working phone or access to the Internet.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Internet services were largely unaffected in areas where basic infrastructure remained, despite the earthquake having damaged portions of several undersea cable systems landing in the affected regions; these systems were able to reroute around affected segments onto redundant links.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Japan, only a few websites were initially unreachable.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no loss of life, although the tsunami resulted in damage to all 18 Mitsubishi F-2 fighter jets of the 21st Fighter Training Squadron.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twelve of the aircraft were scrapped, while the remaining six were slated for repair at a cost of 80 billion yen ($1 billion), exceeding the original cost of the aircraft.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] After the tsunami, elements of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force put to sea without orders and started rescuing those who had been washed out to sea.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunami plans were for the Japan Self-Defense Forces assets to be led, directed, and coordinated by local civic governments.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, the earthquake destroyed town halls (the seat of local municipal government), police, and fire services in many places, so the military not only had to respond to but also command rescues.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Stone monuments at the UNESCO World Heritage Site: Shrines and Temples of Nikkō were toppled.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Tokyo, there was damage to Koishikawa Kōrakuen, Rikugien, Hamarikyū Onshi Teien, and the walls of Edo Castle.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Information on the condition of collections held by museums, libraries and archives is still incomplete.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no damage to the Historic Monuments and Sites of Hiraizumi in Iwate Prefecture, and the recommendation for their inscription on the UNESCO World Heritage List in June was seized upon as a symbol of international recognition and recovery.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the earthquake and tsunami included a humanitarian crisis and a major economic impact.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami resulted in over 340,000 displaced people in the Tōhoku region, and shortages of food, water, shelter, medicine, and fuel for survivors.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In response, the Japanese government mobilized the Self-Defense Forces (under Joint Task Force – Tōhoku, led by Lieutenant General Eiji Kimizuka), while many countries sent search and rescue teams to help search for survivors.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Aid organizations in Japan and worldwide responded, with the Japanese Red Cross reporting $1 billion in donations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The economic impact included immediate problems, with industrial production suspended in many factories, and the longer term issue of the cost of rebuilding, which has been estimated at ¥10 trillion ($122 billion).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In comparison to the 1995 Great Hanshin earthquake, the East Japan earthquake brought serious damage to an extremely wide range.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the twin disasters left Japan's coastal cities and towns with nearly 25 million tons of debris.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki alone, there were 17 trash collection sites 180 meters (590 ft) long and at least 4.5 meters (15 ft) high.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An official in the city's government trash disposal department estimated that it would take three years to empty these sites.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In April 2015, authorities off the coast of Oregon discovered debris that was thought to be from a boat destroyed during the tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The cargo contained yellowtail amberjack, a species of fish that lives off the coast of Japan, still alive.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] KGW estimates that more than 1 million tons of debris still remain in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2016, a memorial was inaugurated by two architects for the victims of the disaster, consisting of a 6.5-square-metre (70 sq ft) structure on a hillside between a temple and a cherry tree in Ishinomaki.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reconstruction of the Tohoku coast was funded and piloted by the Japanese government.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Structural adaptation to tsunamis was largely based on building higher seawalls, although seawalls proved largely ineffective in 2011, and the new seawalls would also not have been high enough.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Seismologists anticipated a very large quake would strike in the same place as the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake—in the Sagami Trough, southwest of Tokyo.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japanese government had tracked plate movements since 1976 in preparation for the so-called Tokai earthquake, predicted to take place in that region.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, occurring as it did 373 km (232 mi) north east of Tokyo, the Tōhoku earthquake came as a surprise to seismologists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] While the Japan Trench was known for creating large quakes, it had not been expected to generate quakes above an 8.0 magnitude.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Also, a tsunami-earthquake with a tsunami magnitude scales (Mt) between 8.6 and 9.0 (Similar to the 1896 Sanriku earthquake, the Mt for the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake was 9.1–9.4) had a 30% chance to occur within 30 years.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The quake gave scientists the opportunity to collect a large amount of data to model the seismic events that took place in great detail.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This data is expected to be used in a variety of ways, providing unprecedented information about how buildings respond to shaking, and other effects.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Gravimetric data from the quake have been used to create a model for increased warning time compared to seismic models, as gravity fields travel faster than seismic waves.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Researchers have also analysed the economic effects of this earthquake and have developed models of the nationwide propagation via interfirm supply networks of the shock that originated in the Tōhoku region.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] After the full extent of the disaster was known, researchers soon launched a project to gather all digital material relating to the disaster into an online searchable archive to form the basis of future research into the events during and after the disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Disasters Digital Archive is presented in English and Japanese and is hosted at the Reischauer Institute of Japanese Studies at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Some of the first research to come from the archive was a 2014 paper from the Digital Methods Initiative in Amsterdam about patterns of Twitter usage around the time of the disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] At this time Japan's Disaster Management Office (Naikakufu Bosai Keikaku) published a bi-lingual guide in Japanese and English, *Disaster Management in Japan*, to outline the several varieties of natural disaster and the preparations being made for the eventuality of each.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Trench Fast Drilling Project, a scientific expedition conducted in 2012–2013, drilled ocean-floor boreholes through the fault zone of the earthquake and gathered important data about the rupture mechanism and physical properties of the fault that caused the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami had a great environmental impact on Japan's eastern coast.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The rarity and magnitude of the earthquake-tsunami prompted researchers Jotaro Urabe, Takao Suzuki, Tatsuki Nishita, and Wataru Makino to study their immediate ecological impacts on intertidal flat communities at Sendai Bay and the Sanriku Ria coast.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Pre- and post-event surveys show a reduction in animal taxon richness and change in taxon composition mainly attributed to the tsunami and its physical impacts.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In particular, sessile epibenthic animals and endobenthic animals both decreased in taxon richness.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Mobile epibenthic animals, such as hermit crabs, were not as affected.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Post-surveys also recorded taxa that were not previously recorded before, suggesting that tsunamis have the potential to introduce species and change taxon composition and local community structure.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The long term ecological impacts at Sendai Bay and the greater east coast of Japan require further study.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The **2014 anti-war protests in Russia** refers to a series of anti-war demonstrations opposing the Russian military intervention in Ukraine that took place in Russia in 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protesters held two anti-war protest rallies on 2 and 15 March 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The latter, known as the **March of Peace** (Russian: Марш Мира, *Marsh Mira*), took place in Moscow a day before the Crimean referendum.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The protests have been the largest in Russia since the 2011–2013 Russian protests by the Russian opposition against the alleged electoral fraud committed by United Russia during the 2011 Russian legislative election.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Reuters reported that around 20,000 people participated in the 15 March demonstrations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 1 March, five people who were picketing next to the Federation Council building against the invasion of Ukraine were arrested.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The next day about 200 people protested at the building of the Russian Ministry of Defense in Moscow against Russian military involvement.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] About 500 people also gathered to protest on the Manezhnaya Square in Moscow and the same number of people on the Saint Isaac's Square in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 2 March, about eleven protesters demonstrated in Yekaterinburg against Russian involvement, with some wrapped in the Ukrainian flag.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 15 March, for a rally in support of Ukraine in Yekaterinburg, according to various sources, between 400 and 600 people left, including the Mayor of the city Yevgeny Roizman.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protests were also held in Chelyabinsk on the same day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The opposition to the military intervention was also expressed by rock musician Andrey Makarevich, who wrote in particular: "You want war with Ukraine?
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] It will not be the way it was with Abkhazia: the folks on the Maidan have been hardened and know what they are fighting for – for their country, their independence. [...] We have to live with them.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] But it's up to them how they want to live".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The Professor of the Department of Philosophy at the Moscow State Institute of International Relations Andrey Zubov was fired for his article in *Vedomosti*, criticizing Russian military intervention.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Andrei Zubov, a professor at the Moscow State Institute of International Relations, who compared Russian actions in Crimea to the Anschluss of Austria, was threatened.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Alexandr Chuyev, the leader of the pro-Kremlin Spravedlivaya Rossiya party, also objected to Russian intervention in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Boris Akunin, popular Russian writer, predicted that Russia's moves would lead to political and economic isolation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protests against the Russian intervention also occurred outside Russian embassies in London, Berlin, Vilnius and Ankara on 2 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protests against the Russian intervention in Crimea also took place in Cologne and outside the Russian Consulate in Bonn, Germany, on 15 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] In August, about a dozen activists were arrested outside the Ukrainian Embassy in Moscow for protesting against Russian president Vladimir Putin.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Another anti-war rally with about 5,000 to 20,000 demonstrators took place on Pushkinskaya Square in Moscow on 21 September 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] *The Washington Post* reported that "tens of thousands" protested the war in Ukraine with a peace march in downtown Moscow "under heavy police supervision".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] There were minor scuffles with pro-Russian supporters, but no serious violence or arrests were reported.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] About a thousand people also gathered outside the Kazan Cathedral in Saint Petersburg to protest against Russia's involvement in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Thousands of people around the world supported this event by holding anti-war demonstrations on the same day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] In the US, San Francisco, New York, Washington, DC, Los Angeles, Seattle, Houston and Boston took part in the protest activities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 19 March 2014, the anti-war congress of Russian intelligentsia took place in Moscow.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 19 March 2014, a group of Russian scientists published an open letter to the Russian Ministry of Communications.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The letter demanded the Ministry to check the television programs of Dmitry Kiselev for signs of extremism and incitement of ethnic hatred.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Following the Russo-Ukrainian war on 24 February 2022, anti-war demonstrations and protests broke out across Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As well as the demonstrations, a number of petitions and open letters have been penned in opposition to the war, and a number of public figures, both cultural and political, have released statements against the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The protests have been met with widespread repression by the Russian authorities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to OVD-Info, at least 14,906 people were detained from 24 February to 13 March 2022.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Human rights organisations and reporters have raised concerns of police brutality during arrests and OVD-Info reported several cases of protesters being tortured under detention.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The government has also moved to crackdown on other forms of opposition to the war, including introducing widespread censorship measures.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Other individuals who signed anti-war petitions have faced reprisals.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After Russian president Vladimir Putin announced a partial mobilization of Russia's military reserves on 21 September, over 2,000 people were detained in mass street protests in the following days.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the afternoon of the invasion, the Investigative Committee of Russia issued a warning to Russians that they would face legal repercussions for joining unsanctioned protests related to "the tense foreign political situation".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The opposition activist Marina Litvinovich called on Instagram for street protests on the evening of 24 February but was detained by police as she left her house.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] That evening, thousands took to the streets in cities across Russia to protest the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The largest demonstrations were in Moscow, where 2,000 protesters gathered near Pushkinskaya Square, and Saint Petersburg, where up to 1,000 protesters gathered.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Hundreds demonstrated in Yekaterinburg, and there were also demonstrations in Chelyabinsk, Nizhny Novgorod, Novosibirsk and Perm, including other cities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of the evening of the day of the invasion, according to the OVD-Info monitor, there had been 1,820 arrests in 58 cities, of which 1,002 were carried out in Moscow.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Russia's interior ministry justified these arrests with "coronavirus restrictions, including on public events".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the following day, 25 February, further protests had continued in Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Saint Petersburg several hundred people gathered in the city center, chanting "No to war!" OVD-Info reported 437 detentions in 26 Russian cities on that day, including 226 in Moscow and 130 in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, some Russian protesters chose to reduce the chances of arrest by staging single-person protests in Moscow and other city squares.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Others gathered in small groups to move more nimbly around the streets.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Yekaterinburg, hundreds gathered, shouting "No to war!".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Throughout the day at least 469 people were arrested in 34 cities, of which around half in Moscow, bringing the total number of arrests to over 3,000.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The protests coincided with the seventh anniversary of the murder of the opposition politician Boris Nemtsov, and arrests took place at an improvised memorial outside the Kremlin where Nemtsov was shot.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Around 1,000 people gathered for a spontaneous anti-war rally near Great Gostiny Dvor in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to OVD-Info, by early Sunday evening, police had detained at least 900 Russians in 44 cities, bringing the total number of arrests to over 4,000 since the war had begun.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of the day, that number had grown to around 2,710 arrests (at least 5,844 in total since the beginning of the war), including at least 1,269 arrests in Moscow and 1,034 in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Members of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, the People's Freedom Party, and Yabloko, spoke out against the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the same day, a van with markings that read "People, wake up!", "This is war", "Putin is scum!" in Russian crashed and caught fire in Pushkinskaya Square.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 1 March, reports and photographs appeared in social media, also republished and confirmed by *Novaya Gazeta*, showing primary school children behind bars, arrested by police in Moscow for laying flowers at the Ukrainian embassy and holding signs saying the repeated "No to war".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A special detention center set up in Yekaterinburg ran out of room for prisoners arrested from protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 2 March, the artist Yelena Osipova, aged 77 and born to survivors of the Siege of Leningrad, was among those arrested at an anti-war protest in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Videos of her arrest were widely shared on social media platforms Twitter and Reddit.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Police action against the protesters continued on the following day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 4 March, the activist Yulia Galyamina was detained and held in custody pending trial, charged with violating the law on public events by trying to organise an anti-war protest.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 5 March, ahead of protests planned for 6 March, police raided, searched and detained hundreds of Russian journalists, politicians and activists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 6 March, there were protests in at least 60 cities, including Vladivostok, Irkutsk and Khabarovsk.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] OVD-Info reported over 5,000 arrests throughout the day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The Russian interior ministry reported over 3,500 detentions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A video showing Kemerovo Oblast governor Sergey Tsivilyov attempting to justify the invasion to protesters that day went viral.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The total number of arrests reached 13,000 overall on 6 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Police ordered the women laying flowers at the Gostiny Dvor in Saint Petersburg to disperse, and made over five arrests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Moscow the Alexander Garden was closed to block access to the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, so flowers were left nearby.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] 11 girls were detained in Moscow's Manezhnaya Square.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At least 93 people, at least 60 of them in Moscow, were detained.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 15 March, Anastasia Parshkova was arrested for standing alone before the Cathedral of Christ the Saviour in Moscow with a placard bearing the words "6th Commandment.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She was taken to the police station, according to the Avtozak Live telegram channel.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The art historian Maria Silina has characterized Parshkova's action – redeploying symbols of the Russian Orthodox Church to critique the alliance between Orthodox religion and military ideology – as an example of détournement typical of contemporary feminist art activism in Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In the week following International Women's Day, several videos went viral on social media showing Russian police arresting protesters for simply holding up a blank sign.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Another arrest which went viral was that of a woman arrested for holding up a small sign that simply read "два слова" ("two words" in Russian).
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of March, mass protests were reported to have largely subsided due to repression from the authorities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some smaller individual acts of opposition against the war continued.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Sochi, Diana Isakova and other activists prepared flyers with QR codes that led to an online text "Time to change!" written by Isakova, criticising Putin as a dictator and calling for citizens to organise and carry out nonviolent resistance against the Putin government.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 17 April, Isakova and her colleagues distributed the flyers.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Isakova was later arrested but was not prosecuted.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The audience staged an anti-war protest at the concert of the Russian group Kis-Kis in Saint Petersburg in May.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Unconfirmed reports circulated about a protest planned for 12 June, Russia Day, which eventually did not take place.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Instead, authorities in Moscow detained 50 people, using facial recognition software.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 21 September, the Vesna movement called for country-wide demonstrations in response to Putin's announcement of partial mobilization of Russia's military reserves, following setbacks for the Russian military during the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kharkiv Oblast.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Multiple small-scale protests followed in several cities, including Moscow, Saint Petersburg, Yekaterinburg, Novosibirsk and Tomsk.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] More than 1,311 protesters in 38 cities had been detained by the end of the day, according to OVD-Info.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 24 September, anti-mobilization rallies organized by Vesna took place in many cities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The rallies were marked by mass detentions not only of protesters, but also of ordinary passers-by.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to OVD-Info, more than 750 people were detained by 22:30 Moscow time.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 25 September, the women of Yakutsk went to a rally under the slogans "We will not give up our husbands", "No to genocide", "No to war".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] People gathered in Uosohhai, a traditional round dance symbolising the blessing of mothers for the safe return of their husbands and sons.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The women were soon dispersed by the security forces.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the same day, residents of Endirey, Khasavyurtovsky District of Dagestan, took part in a rally against mobilization.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The police fired live rounds into the air in an attempt to disperse the rally.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In the evening of 25 September, a rally was held in Makhachkala, the capital of Dagestan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At the rally, protesters clashed with the police, who in turn opened fire into the air.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of the day, the protest was dispersed by Rosgvardia troops.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As well as protests, activists have also posted anti-war stickers around neighbourhoods, have written anti-war messages on banknotes, and have hung posters that mimic official missing person posters, but that instead contain information about Russian soldiers that have been killed in the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The artist Alexandra Skochilenko was arrested for allegedly replacing supermarket labels with messages protesting the Mariupol theatre airstrike, and jailed for eight weeks pending trial under the Russian fake news laws.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Voronezh and Lukhovitsy, cases of arson of military enlistment offices and police departments in Krasnoyarsk and Smolensk were recorded.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Molotov cocktails were used in all of them.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As of beginning-June, at least 15 cases of arson directed at military recruitment centres had been recorded.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 24 March, a video was released on TikTok showing a protester throwing Molotov cocktails at the Moscow Kremlin walls.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 28 March, Moscow student Anastasia Levashova was sentenced to two years in prison for having thrown a Molotov cocktail at police during an anti-war rally.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At least four teachers have been arrested after criticising the invasion in their classrooms.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 14 March, Marina Ovsyannikova, an editor at Channel One Russia, disrupted the set of the channel's main news program *Vremya* during prime time by holding up a sign with an anti-war message.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Do not believe the propaganda, here you are being lied to.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ovsyannikova, the daughter of a Ukrainian father and a Russian mother, also released a pre-recorded video at OVD-Info in which she expressed shame for her part in spreading "Kremlin propaganda" at Channel One.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She was detained by police later that evening and was released, according to TASS.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ovsyannikova was detained and later released again on 17 July after staging a lone protest at the Sophia Embankment, in front of the Kremlin, two days prior.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Others have taken to attempt to remove symbols of pro-Russian actions, such as the letter Z.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A man, who later fled to Armenia, reportedly stopped a car with the letter Z on its windscreen with a shovel and ordered the car's inhabitants to rip it off.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 September, a gunman opened fire at a draft office in Irkutsk Oblast, injuring one senior official.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 8 May 2023, the Yav Art Group presented an installation titled "Russian Cyberpunk", where prostheses painted with Gzhel patterns were attached to human silhouettes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The project was swiftly dismantled by authorities after its installation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some Russian soldiers have been reported to have disobeyed orders to join the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 12 March, it was reported that around 80 marines had refused to fight after being deployed to Kherson and were returned to Crimea.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 7 April, Pskov newspaper Pskovskaya Gubernia reported that around 60 Russian paratroopers in Belarus had refused such orders, further reporting that Russian commanders were blocking attempts by soldiers to resign from the Russian Armed Forces and referring those soldiers to prosecutors instead.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In the weeks preceding the invasion, there were signs that anti-war sentiment was growing in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At the beginning of February, over 150 prominent Russian activists, authors, and academics signed an open letter, 'If Only There Is No War!', protesting the "party of war in the Russian leadership" and state media.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the invasion, Russian Nobel Peace Prize winner Dmitry Muratov announced that the *Novaya Gazeta* newspaper would publish its next edition in both Ukrainian and Russian.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Another letter condemning the war was signed by over 250 scientists, and a third open letter was signed by almost 200 municipal council members in Moscow and other cities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 24 February, human rights activist Lev Ponomaryov started an online petition to protest against the invasion, garnering 289,000 signatures by the end of the day.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By 1 March, the petition had gathered more than a million votes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, a petition for the impeachment of Putin was published by a Russian citizen on the Change.org website, gathering more than 200,000 signatures by the end of 27 February.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some of the petition signers lost their jobs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] More than 30,000 technology workers, 6,000 medical workers, 3,400 architects, more than 4,300 teachers, more than 17,000 artists, 5,000 scientists, and 2,000 actors, directors, and other creative figures signed open letters calling for Putin's government to stop the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some Russians who signed petitions against Russia's war in Ukraine lost their jobs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] They are dying through the fault of those who preferred weapons instead of peaceful diplomacy. ....
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Igor Kochetkov, the head of the Russian LGBT Network, launched an open letter against the war and stating that "There are a lot of problems in our country, including the spread of anti-human ideas, which often come from high-ranking officials.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Let's start 'denazification' with them." The open letter received signatures from 150 Russian LGBT+ rights activists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Representatives of Russian arts and culture workers initiated an open letter expressing solidarity with the Ukrainian people and protesting against the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As of 23:00 Moscow time on 27 February 2022, the letter was signed by 17,000 people.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Lev Ponomaryov initiated a petition titled "Остановить войну с Украиной! – Нет войне" ("Stop the war with Ukraine! – No to war").
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By 4 March, the petition had been signed by more than 1.18 million Russians.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In April 2023, anti-Kremlin activists gathered at a Paris rally organised by Navalny's team and urged the European Union (EU) to ban Svetlana Maniovich, ex-wife of Timur Ivanov, from living in Europe and freeze her assets.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ivanov had already been sanctioned by the EU in October 2022, and was considered by the EU to be responsible for the Russian war effort at large.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Relatives of some Russian officials who justify Russia's war against Ukraine have also expressed their disagreement with the Kremlin's decision through the hashtag "No to war!".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Among them was Liza Peskova, the daughter of the official representative of the Kremlin Dmitry Peskov.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The white-blue-white flag is an anti-war symbol created by removing the red from the Russian flag.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to anti-war protesters, the red represented blood and violence, and the flag attempts to evoke the legacy of the historic Novgorod Republic as an example of democracy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] However, not all protesters appreciated the flag.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Maria Motuznaya (an opposition activist) had criticised the justification for the removal red stripe of the flag.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A version of the Russian national anthem proposed in early 1917 after the February Revolution that overthrew the monarchy and turned Russia into a republic that lasted until October 1917.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the Civil War, it was used by Russian emigration, including on radio broadcasting to dissidents in the Soviet Union.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In 2022, the song again became popular among supporters of the anti-war movement.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The slogan "Russia will be free", already popular among the Russian opposition has been adopted by the anti-war protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some protesters have used green ribbons as a symbol of opposition to the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Both the Russian United Democratic "Yabloko" Party and the Party of People's Freedom condemned the impending invasion of Ukraine several days before 24 February 2022.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Both of these parties opposed the illegal annexation of Crimea and hold moderately pro-Ukrainian positions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The Yabloko party published a petition demanding the withdrawal of troops from the Ukrainian-Russian border on 13 February 2022.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Although the party continues to legally exist, dozens of Yabloko members, politicians, and activists have been arrested or detained since 24 February.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The Communist Party of the Russian Federation (KPRF) officially supports the invasion and is often characterized as a controlled opposition to Putin's government, however, some youth and left-wing factions within the party have opposed the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Two KPRF deputies have spoken up against the war: Mikhail Matveyev and Oleg Smolin.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] KPRF senator Vyacheslav Markhayev has also spoken against the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 27 May 2022, two KPRF lawmakers from the Legislative Assembly of Primorsky Krai were kicked out of the oblast's KPRF group and two others were reprimanded by the party after presenting a statement in opposition to the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 15 February, the website of Russian political party New People, which is also known as a controlled opposition and a spoiler party, released a statement by Sardana Avksentyeva, condemning the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the start of the invasion, leader of the party, Alexey Nechayev, made statements in support of military action.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Avksentyeva's anti-war statement was deleted, and she herself later supported the invasion: "And I feel that today we must give our military an opportunity to complete their work...
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] However, one of the New People deputies of the State Duma, Sangadji Tarbaev, has publicly condemned the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Valery Gartung, also a State Duma deputy and a member of A Just Russia — For Truth party (which supports the invasion), also denounced it in Facebook, and later commented his post to Republic.ru.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Mikhail Gorbachev, the last CPSU General Secretary and the head of state of the Soviet Union, stated that "everything possible must be done to stop the threat of a nuclear war".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, the Gorbachev Foundation stated: "In connection with Russia's military operation in Ukraine, begun on February 24, we affirm the need for an early cessation of hostilities and immediate start of peace negotiations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 27 February, Russian politician Lyudmila Narusova, a member of the Federation Council, stated in a television interview: "I do not identify myself with those representatives of the state that speak out in favor of the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] I think they themselves do not know what they are doing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] They are following orders without thinking." Arkady Dvorkovich, who served as a Deputy Prime Minister from 2012 to 2018, condemned Russia's invasion of Ukraine and said that "Wars are the worst things one might face in life...including this war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] My thoughts are with Ukrainian civilians." On 23 March, Putin's longtime advisor and Russian climate envoy Anatoly Chubais resigned from his position and left Russia due to his opposition to the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Alexei Navalny, the opposition leader who was imprisoned in January 2021, called Putin an "obviously insane tsar" and urged Russians to continue daily street protests: "Go out onto the main square of your city every weekday at 19.00 and at 14.00 at weekends and on holidays".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Other groups which have expressed their opposition to the war include the Revolutionary Workers Party, the Libertarian Party of Russia, Socialist Alternative, the Pirate Party of Russia, the United Communist Party, the Left Bloc and Autonomous Action.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ukrainian-born Russian politician and diplomat Natalia Poklonskaya, who rose to prominence during Russia's annexation of Crimea, called the invasion a catastrophe, also adding "People are dying, houses and entire cities are destroyed [leaving] millions of refugees.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] My two native countries are killing each other, that's not what I wanted and it's not what I want".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She also said that Ukraine's society has "changed" in the eight years since the war in Donbas with pro-Russian separatists was ongoing and that Ukrainians "would not greet Russia with flowers".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She also criticized the Z military symbol.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to *The Moscow Times*, Poklonskaya's break with Russia's official line that the Russian invasion of Ukraine is a "special military operation" to "de-Nazify and demilitarize" Ukraine was practically unheard of for a sitting official.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 9 September, seven council members from Smolninsky District Council in St.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Petersburg passed a resolution which called on the State Duma to impeach president Putin for "high treason" due to his handling of the war in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the invasion began on 24 February, several Russian celebrities, including pop star Valery Meladze, television host Ivan Urgant and television presenter Ksenia Sobchak, unambiguously criticized it on social media.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The comedian and television presenter Maxim Galkin and television comedian Alexander Gudkov also condemned the war, as did actress Chulpan Khamatova and actor Konstantin Khabensky.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ukrainian-born pop star Svetlana Loboda asked "How is this possible?
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Lord, stop all this!" Figure skater Evgenia Medvedeva called for "this all [to end] as soon as possible, like a bad dream".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Chess player Yan Nepomniachtchi tweeted in protest: "History has seen many Black Thursdays.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] But today is blacker than the others. #saynotowar".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Tennis world number one Daniil Medvedev and world number seven Andrey Rublev both spoke out in favour of peace on the day of the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the following day Rublev wrote "No war please" on the camera after winning his match.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The hip-hop artist Oxxxymiron cancelled upcoming shows and called for mass protest, calling the invasion "a crime and a catastrophe".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Yelena Kovalskaya resigned as director of the state-owned Meyerhold Theater Center, writing that it was "impossible to work for a murderer and receive salary from him".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Pianist and composer Evgeny Kissin described Russia's invasion as a crime that cannot be justified.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The pianist Alexander Melnikov said "I'm furious with [Putin's government] for making me feel guilty about being Russian." Pop singer Sergey Lazarev called for the war to stop.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 25 February, the ice hockey star Alex Ovechkin, an ardent Putin supporter, made an ambiguous statement against the war without mentioning Ukraine or Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, Georgian basketball player Tornike Shengelia announced he was prematurely terminating his contract with CSKA Moscow "in protest against Russia's invasion of Ukraine".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Citing the club's historical links to the Red Army, Shengelia said: "I do not consider it possible to continue playing for the Russian army club".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Liza Peskova, the daughter of Putin's spokesman Dmitry Peskov, shared an image of the "No to war" hashtag on her Instagram story but then quickly deleted it and criticized the protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Russia's richest billionaire, Mikhail Fridman, called for the "bloodshed to end".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] "It is terrible that Ukrainians and Russians are dying, people are suffering hardships, the economy is collapsing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By 27 February, several prominent Russian public figures living in exile had organized the Anti-War Committee of Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Mikhail Shishkin, winner of the 2000 Russian Booker Prize, wrote on *The Guardian* that "Putin is committing monstrous crimes in the name of my people, my country, and me" and saying that "in Putin's Russia it's impossible to breathe.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Actor Danila Kozlovsky posted several Instagram posts condemning the war, sharing an image of a crying refugee and using the "*Нет войне!*"-hashtag.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In a post on 27 February, Kozlovsky admitted to and apologized for his indifference to Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Timur Bekmambetov, director of hits such as *Night Watch*, condemned the invasion in an interview with Deadline.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Unconfirmed reports states that Bekmambetov (who is based in Los Angeles) and his family had cut ties with Russia completely, following the sale his production company Bazelevs Company.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 21 March, rock musician Zemfira released an anti-war music video to her 2017 song "Don't Shoot", while also removing all of her other songs from her YouTube channel.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The video contained footage of Russia's military assault on Ukraine and of anti-war protests in Moscow.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In May 2022, rock singer Yuri Shevchuk was prosecuted after speaking out against Putin and the war in Ukraine at a concert in Ufa.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] He said that "people of Ukraine are being murdered" and "our boys are dying over there" due to "some Napoleonic plans of another Caesar of ours".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In October 2022, Russian actor Artur Smolyaninov was charged for "discrediting" the Russian military – that was after his anti-war statements and after he had left Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] He commented; "The laws of this state do not exist for me.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The founders of the "Immortal Regiment" commemoration movement, in which ordinary Russians carry photographs of veteran family members in marches around Russia held annually to mark WWII Victory Day on 9 May, addressed Vladimir Putin in a statement, asking him to "stop the bloodshed".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Svetlana Golub, head of the Union of the Committees of Soldiers' Mothers of Russia told The Guardian that "Wars always lead to deaths.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] From the many conversations I have been sent between soldiers and their families, I believe many Russians have already died...
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Conflicts always mean lots of suffering.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 3 March, the multinational company Lukoil, the second largest company in Russia after Gazprom, called for a ceasefire and diplomatic means to solve the conflict.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A spokesperson for the United Nations condemned the "arbitrary arrests" of protesters, and called for their immediate release.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russia's interior ministry justified the arrests due to the "coronavirus restrictions, including on public events" that remained in place.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russian authorities warned Russians of legal repercussions for joining anti-war protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Works by Russian authors critical of the war (ex.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Vladimir Sorokin, Dmitry Bykov, Boris Akunin) have been subject to censorship in the form of being withdrawn from many Russian bookstores.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 1 March, the Moscow radio station Echo of Moscow, as well as the independent channel TV Rain, was forced off air for having aired opposition to the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] After completing their final broadcast, TV Rain put on a loop of *Swan Lake*, echoing the efforts of Soviet authorities to bury bad news, including the 1991 attempted coup d'état as the USSR was breaking up.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 4 March, the Russian parliament passed a law aimed at stifling reporting on and opposition to the war which punishes citizens with up to 15 years in jail for spreading "fake information" about the Russian military and its operations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] This law also makes it illegal "to make calls against the use of Russian troops to protect the interests of Russia" or "for discrediting such use" with a penalty possible of up to three years in prison.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The same provision applies to calls for sanctions against Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] This law effectively criminalizes any public opposition to or independent news reporting about the war against Ukraine and could make it a crime to simply call the war a "war" — the Kremlin says it is a "special military operation" — on social media or in a news article or broadcast.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Later that day, Putin signed the bill into law; he also signed into law a bill that would allow fines or prison sentences of up to 3 years for those calling for sanctions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Mediazona defiantly promised to continue, providing tips to evade censorship.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 11 March, Roskomnadzor blocked the websites of Amnesty International as well as that of Russian election monitoring group Golos.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to the news website Agentstvo, over 150 journalists left Russia by 7 March since Putin signed the bill into law.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 16 March, Russian socialite and food blogger Veronika Belotserkovskaya became the first individual charged under Russia's new "false information" law.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 25 March, Russian journalist Izabella Yevloyeva was charged under the "fakes law" after sharing a post on social media that described the "Z" symbol as being "synonymous with aggression, death, pain and shameless manipulation".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Sergei Klokov, a Moscow policeman with Ukrainian roots, who is originally from Bucha, Kyiv Oblast, was arrested after he told colleagues what he had heard from his father and Ukrainian family friends about the Russian invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to OVD-Info, over 400 people were detained or fined by April under the laws prohibiting "fake" information about the military.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The use of fake messages was claimed to have been used by Russian authorities by at least one Russian anti-war protester.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] He claimed that shortly after he was released from detention strange anti-war messages appeared on his phone, and had feared the messages were an attempt to incriminate him before he could leave the country.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] More than 2,000 people were detained or fined by May 2022 under the laws prohibiting "fake" information about the military.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] By early June, 53 criminal cases had been opened.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In July 2022, Alexei Gorinov, a member of the Krasnoselsky district council in Moscow, was sentenced to seven years in prison after making anti-war comments at a council meeting in March, including stating that Russia was waging a war of aggression against Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Lawyer Pavel Chikov said that this was the first jail term under the new law.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In August 2022, the former mayor of Yekaterinburg, Yevgeny Roizman, was detained by police where he said he was being charged with "discrediting" the military.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Roizman was previously fined three times under the same law.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to OVD-Info, the total number of people detained across Russia after six months is around 16,500, with over 3,800 being charged with offenses that carry fines, and at least 224 facing criminal prosecution.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In December 2022, a Moscow court sentenced opposition politician Ilya Yashin to eight years and six months imprisonment for his statements about the circumstances of the killings in Bucha on charges of "spreading false information" about the armed forces.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] His punishment was the harshest given under the new laws.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] OVD-Info said that over 380 others were on trial for similar charges.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In January 2023, an opposition deputy of the Saint Petersburg Legislative Assembly, Boris Vishnevskiy, as well as a former deputy, Maxim Reznik, were charged with discrediting the armed forces over "materials about the city of Bucha" and a "large number of killed civilians".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In March 2023, a new law was signed establishing criminal liability for "discrediting" and spreading "fakes" against mercenaries and volunteers fighting for Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Article 280.3 ("discrediting") was amended to increase the maximum prison term from five years to seven years.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Article 207.3 ("fakes") was amended to increase terms from three years to five years under the first part of the law, with the second and third parts remaining unchanged, at 10 and 15 years, respectively.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty has reported that students in some universities have been threatened with expulsion over acts of anti-war protest.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In early March, the student union of Saint Petersburg State University reported that the university has expelled at least 13 students for taking part in anti-war protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A number of anti-war activists and independent journalists in Russia have had their homes targeted with vandalism since the beginning of the invasion, including having manure and messages calling them traitors left outside their doors.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The Z symbol, which has achieved prominence in Russian popular culture as a symbol of support for the war, in part through state promotion of the symbol, has also been used to graffiti the homes of several anti-war activists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to *The Moscow Times*, Russian authorities and pro-government figures have actively encouraged reporting other citizens, including friends and family, for "anti-Russian" activities including anti-war statements.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russian NGO OVD-Info reported that it had confirmed at least 30 cases of protesters being beaten by police on the weekend of 5–6 March, as well as several cases of arrested protesters being tortured in detention, while saying that "it is likely that this number is much higher.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Mediazona has further reported that women who have been arrested have been subjected to threats of sexual violence, that arrested gender-non-conforming protesters have been ridiculed, and that police sprayed some detainees in the face with antiseptic solutions.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A number of people affiliated with the Russian government have spoken out against the protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Putin's press secretary, Dmitry Peskov, stated that "now is not the time to be divided.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Chairman of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin denounced Russians who oppose the war as "traitors".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 16 March 2022, Russian President Vladimir Putin issued a warning to Russian "traitors" who he said the West wanted to use as a "fifth column" to destroy Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russian authorities encouraged Russians to report their friends, colleagues and family members to the police for expressing opposition to the war in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Since the beginning of the invasion, more than 300,000 Russians have fled the country, particularly citizens who are opposed to the war, in response to increasing repression and rumours of conscription and martial law.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Journalist Boris Grozovski published a Facebook post saying that "We are not tourists, dear citizens of Georgia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Personally, I was wanted by the police in Russia for distributing anti-war petitions...
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] We ran not from bullets, bombs and missiles, but from prison.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Bolshoi Theater ballerina Olga Smirnova left Russia to continue her career in the Netherlands in protest of the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] By early April, an estimated 100,000 Russians had fled Russia to Georgia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] After three weeks of war, around 14,000 were said to have left for Turkey.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Tens of thousands went to Armenia; by 24 May an estimated 108,000 Russian citizens having fled to the country, or Nordic states such as Finland.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Thousands are said to have gone to Uzbekistan.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A state-run poll published on 28 February by the Russian Public Opinion Research Center claimed that 68% of Russians supported the "special military operation", 22% opposed, and 10% found it difficult to answer.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Later on, a series of four online polls by Alexei Navalny's Anti-Corruption Foundation claimed to show sentiment rapidly shifting among Moscow residents.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Between 25 February and 3 March, those blaming Russia for the war increased from 14% to 36%, with 79% now in favour of stopping the conflict and engaging in peace negotiation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The proportion of respondents who considered Russia an "aggressor" increased from 29% to 53%, while the share of those considering Russia a "peace-maker" fell by half from 25% to 12%.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] From 26 to 28 February 2022, a survey conducted by the independent research group Russian Field found that 58.8% of respondents supported the "special military operation" in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to the poll, in the group of 18-to-24-year-olds, only 29% supported the "special military operation".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A poll by the independent Levada Center published on 30 March saw Putin's approval rating jump from 71% in February to 83% in March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A study by researchers affiliated with the London School of Economics found that stated support for the war among Russians dropped from 68% to 53% when asked indirectly about the invasion in polls.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Many respondents do not want to answer pollsters' questions for fear of negative consequences.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In March 2022, when a Russian opposition politician Maxim Katz and a group of Russian researchers commissioned a poll on Russians' attitudes toward the war in Ukraine, 29,400 of the 31,000 people they called refused to answer after hearing the subject matter in question.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Many have been planned through personal networks and social media posts.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In some cases, opponents of the war have simply travelled to their nearest city centre in the hope of finding like-minded citizens.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Several commentators have noted the significant presence of youth in the anti-war protests in Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Commentators have also noted the significant role of women in the protests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] One reason many Russians have supported the "special military operation" in Ukraine has to do with the propaganda and disinformation being sown by the Kremlin.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Some observers noted what they described as a "generational struggle" among Russians over perception of the war, with younger Russians more likely opposed to the war and older Russians more likely to accept the narrative presented by state-controlled media in Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The effect of international sanctions and condemnation of the war at domestic anti-war protests has been debated.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In early March 2022, Kremlinologist Lilia Shevtsova stated that "the 'Crimea effect' is vanishing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The war in Ukraine creates 'our' casualties – this will have an impact.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Moreover, in 2008 and 2014, the wars were relatively short and they ended with 'our' victory.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] As of December 2023, support for Putin's war in Ukraine among Russians hit an all-time low.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] With the beginning of mobilization in Russia in September 2022 during the Russo-Ukrainian war, anti-war and anti-mobilization protests broke out in the Russian Far East, mostly performed by women.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] Former Mongolian President Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj protested against usage of ethnic minorities such as the Buryats, Tuvans, and Kalmyks as cannon fodder, and invited them to Mongolia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] The Tuvans belong to Turkic peoples but are also regarded in Mongolia as one of the Uriankhai peoples.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] Women protested in Ordzhonikidze Square, in Yakutsk.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] Some elderly men were conscripted by mistake.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] Small groups protested in Ulan-Ude under handwritten signs "No war!
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] No mobilization!" and "Our husbands, fathers and brothers don’t want to kill other husbands and fathers." The Free Buryatia Foundation collects appeals for help from families of mobilised men.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] According to Alexandra Garmazhapova, president of the foundation, some local people try to go to Mongolia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] Marina Salomatova, a member of the "Transbaikal Civil Solidarity", has been arrested in Chita, Zabaykalsky Krai.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-far-eastern-protests] Women protested against mobilization in Kyzyl, 20 of them were arrested.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The **anti-nuclear movement** is a social movement that opposes various nuclear technologies.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some direct action groups, environmental movements, and professional organisations have identified themselves with the movement at the local, national, or international level.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Major anti-nuclear groups include Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, Friends of the Earth, Greenpeace, International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War, Peace Action, Seneca Women's Encampment for a Future of Peace and Justice and the Nuclear Information and Resource Service.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The movement's initial objective was nuclear disarmament, though since the late 1960s, opposition has also included the use of nuclear power.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Many anti-nuclear groups oppose both nuclear power and nuclear weapons.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The formation of green parties in the 1970s and 1980s was often a direct result of anti-nuclear politics.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Scientists and diplomats have debated nuclear weapons policy since before the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The public became concerned about nuclear weapons testing from about 1954, following extensive nuclear testing, including the Castle Bravo disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1963, many countries ratified the Partial Test Ban Treaty, which prohibited atmospheric nuclear testing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some local opposition to nuclear power emerged in the early 1960s.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the late 1960s some members of the scientific community began to express their concerns.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the early 1970s, there were large protests about the proposed Wyhl Nuclear Power Plant, in southern Germany.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The project was cancelled in 1975, and anti-nuclear success at Wyhl inspired opposition to nuclear power in other parts of Europe and North America.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] A protest against nuclear power occurred in July 1977 in Bilbao, Spain, with up to 200,000 people in attendance.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Following the Three Mile Island accident in 1979, an anti-nuclear protest was held in New York City, involving 200,000 people.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1981, Germany's largest anti-nuclear power demonstration took place to protest against the Brokdorf Nuclear Power Plant west of Hamburg; some 100,000 people came face to face with 10,000 police officers.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The largest protest was held on 12 June 1982, when one million people demonstrated in New York City against nuclear weapons.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] A 1983 nuclear weapons protest in West Berlin had about 600,000 participants.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In May 1986, following the Chernobyl disaster, an estimated 150,000 to 200,000 people marched in Rome to protest against the Italian nuclear program.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In Australia, unions, peace activists, and environmentalists opposed uranium mining from the 1970s onwards, and rallies bringing together hundreds of thousands of people to oppose nuclear weapons peaked in the mid- 1980s.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the US, public opposition preceded the shutdown of the Shoreham, Yankee Rowe, Millstone 1, Rancho Seco, Maine Yankee, and many other nuclear power plants.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] For many years after the 1986 Chernobyl disaster, nuclear power was off the policy agenda in most countries, and the anti-nuclear power movement seemed to have won its case, so some anti-nuclear groups disbanded.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the 2000s, however, following public relations activities by the nuclear industry, advances in nuclear reactor designs, and concerns about climate change, nuclear power issues came back into energy policy discussions in some countries.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The 2011 Fukushima nuclear accident subsequently undermined the nuclear power industry's proposed renaissance and revived opposition to nuclear power worldwide, putting governments on the defensive.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As of 2016, countries such as Australia, Austria, Denmark, Greece, Malaysia, New Zealand, and Norway have no nuclear power stations and remain opposed to nuclear power.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Germany, Italy, Spain, and Switzerland are phasing-out nuclear power.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Sweden formerly had a nuclear phase-out policy, aiming to end nuclear power generation in Sweden by 2010.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] On 5 February 2009, the Government of Sweden announced an agreement allowing for the replacement of existing reactors, effectively ending the phase-out policy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Globally, the number of operable reactors has remained nearly the same over the last 30 years, and nuclear electricity production has been steadily growing since the Fukushima disaster.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The application of nuclear technology, as a source of energy and as an instrument of war, has been controversial.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] These issues are discussed in nuclear weapons debate, nuclear power debate, and uranium mining debate.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The public became concerned about nuclear weapons testing from about 1954, following extensive nuclear testing in the Pacific, with some calling it nuclear imperialism and colonialism.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1961, at the height of the Cold War, about 50,000 women brought together by Women Strike for Peace marched in 60 cities in the United States to demonstrate against nuclear weapons.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1963, many countries ratified the Partial Test Ban Treaty which prohibited atmospheric nuclear testing.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some local opposition to nuclear power emerged in the early 1960s, and, in the late 1960s, some members of the scientific community began expressing their concerns.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the early 1970s, there were large protests about the proposed Wyhl Nuclear Power Plant in southern Germany.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Nuclear power became an issue of major public protest in the 1970s.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The fossil fuel industry starting from the 1950s was engaging in campaigns against the nuclear industry which it perceived as a threat to their commercial interests.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Groups like the Sierra Club, Environmental Defense Fund and Natural Resources Defense Council are receiving grants from other fossil fuel companies.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As of 2011, a strategy paper released by Greenpeace titled "Battle of Grids" proposed gradual replacement of nuclear power by fossil gas plants which would provide "flexible backup for wind and solar power".
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] However, Greenpeace has since distanced itself from advocating for fossil gas, instead proposing grid energy storage as a solution to issues caused by intermittent renewable energy.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In Germany, the Energiewende, which was advertised as a shift to renewable energy but included a gradual phaseout of nuclear power from 2000 to the end of 2022, caused, among other things, a rise in fossil gas power production from 49.2 TWh in 2000 to 94.7 TWh in 2020.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the same interval total electricity generation barely changed (576.6 TWh in 2000 vs 574.2 TWh in 2020) while it did rise and fall in the meantime, reaching a peak of 652.9 TWh in 2017.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As much of that fossil gas was, and remains, imported from Russia, controversial pipeline projects like Nord Stream 1 were built to meet rising German gas demand.
[src:anti-nuclear-movement/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine it came to light that significant amounts of Russian lobbying was involved in both the continued anti-nuclear movement in Germany and the anti-fracking movement.
